1
00:00:14,014 --> 00:00:18,318
A makeover project
for your most unhinged leftovers.

2
00:00:18,385 --> 00:00:21,955
The best chefs in Korea will
turn your fridge inside out.

3
00:00:22,022 --> 00:00:24,424
The classy cooking show has returned.

4
00:00:24,491 --> 00:00:26,993
<i>-Chef & My Fridge!</i>
<i>-My Fridge!</i>

5
00:00:29,596 --> 00:00:31,598
Welcome, everyone.

6
00:00:31,664 --> 00:00:33,967
I've been hearing many good news

7
00:00:34,034 --> 00:00:35,835
regarding our show.

8
00:00:35,902 --> 00:00:37,237
Here's news hot from the oven.

9
00:00:37,303 --> 00:00:39,272
<i>Chef & My Fridge</i>

10
00:00:39,339 --> 00:00:43,176
has been scheduled regularly
on a TV channel in Taiwan.

11
00:00:43,777 --> 00:00:46,579
So they didn't
just buy the right to show it,

12
00:00:46,646 --> 00:00:49,516
-but it's scheduled?
-It'll be aired on TV in Taiwan

13
00:00:49,582 --> 00:00:51,885
with subtitles, of course.

14
00:00:51,951 --> 00:00:52,852
Blah blah.

15
00:00:52,919 --> 00:00:54,087
Blah blah?

16
00:00:54,154 --> 00:00:56,056
<i>Hello, my name is Kim Poong.</i>

17
00:00:56,122 --> 00:00:57,590
It's something like that.

18
00:00:57,657 --> 00:01:01,394
I keep hearing updates
that <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> is

19
00:01:01,461 --> 00:01:03,363
gaining popularity all around Asia.

20
00:01:03,930 --> 00:01:07,767
I'm sure our chefs must've noticed
your rising popularity too.

21
00:01:07,834 --> 00:01:10,503
I've been noticing it a lot.

22
00:01:10,570 --> 00:01:14,040
I've had people tell me
that they saw my face

23
00:01:14,107 --> 00:01:16,042
in a taxi in Taiwan.

24
00:01:16,109 --> 00:01:17,343
Really?

25
00:01:17,410 --> 00:01:19,312
-And Chef Ji-sun.
-Chef Ji-sun?

26
00:01:19,379 --> 00:01:21,781
She goes to Taiwan once a week.

27
00:01:21,848 --> 00:01:23,817
-Really? Why?
-Yes.

28
00:01:23,883 --> 00:01:26,252
<i>I hold lots of events</i>
<i>and shoot advertisements.</i>

29
00:01:26,319 --> 00:01:28,121
<i>I was there last week,</i>
<i>and I'm going next week too.</i>

30
00:01:28,855 --> 00:01:31,057
Many people there watch <i>Chef & My Fridge,</i>

31
00:01:31,124 --> 00:01:32,926
so they even mentioned
my victory last time.

32
00:01:32,992 --> 00:01:35,195
-This is how popular we are.
-Yes.

33
00:01:35,261 --> 00:01:37,931
Chef Sung-jun, can you tell us
about Hong Kong?

34
00:01:37,997 --> 00:01:40,366
-It's awkward for me to say it, though.
-Right.

35
00:01:40,433 --> 00:01:42,135
But still, say it.

36
00:01:42,202 --> 00:01:44,504
I've shot an advertisement there.

37
00:01:44,571 --> 00:01:47,507
-Really?
-We're pretty global.

38
00:01:47,574 --> 00:01:50,777
I always put on a face mask when I go out.

39
00:01:50,844 --> 00:01:52,912
MOCKING LAUGHTER

40
00:01:52,979 --> 00:01:54,547
But everyone still recognized me.

41
00:01:54,614 --> 00:01:56,082
-Even with the face mask?
-Yes.

42
00:01:56,149 --> 00:01:59,085
Maybe it's because the mask was too small.

43
00:01:59,152 --> 00:02:00,253
A REASONABLE DOUBT(?)

44
00:02:00,320 --> 00:02:01,488
The mask was…

45
00:02:01,554 --> 00:02:05,024
I kept it on all the time,
but it wasn't easy to go unnoticed.

46
00:02:05,091 --> 00:02:07,293
Maybe he uses the kids' size on purpose.

47
00:02:07,360 --> 00:02:10,630
-An update from Malaysia.
-Malaysia too?

48
00:02:10,697 --> 00:02:13,867
Chef Jong-won went there for an event,

49
00:02:13,933 --> 00:02:16,002
and the tickets were sold out
in one minute.

50
00:02:16,069 --> 00:02:17,537
-Whoa.
-Is this true?

51
00:02:17,604 --> 00:02:20,440
Yes, I worked with the Korean government

52
00:02:20,507 --> 00:02:22,775
<i>for a publicity event.</i>

53
00:02:22,842 --> 00:02:26,813
And the visitors came and said
they saw me on <i>Chef & My Fridge.</i>

54
00:02:26,880 --> 00:02:30,016
-That's the English title.
-Yes, the English one.

55
00:02:30,083 --> 00:02:33,219
They also said they knew me
as something-something.

56
00:02:33,286 --> 00:02:36,589
I tried to figure out what it was,
and they called me the good vibes guy.

57
00:02:36,656 --> 00:02:39,325
-The good vibes guy?
-Good vibes?

58
00:02:39,392 --> 00:02:41,895
-The good vibes guy.
-The guy with good vibes.

59
00:02:41,961 --> 00:02:45,031
-How about the two against him?
-Bad vibes?

60
00:02:45,098 --> 00:02:47,934
-They're anti-good vibes.
-Anti-good vibes?

61
00:02:48,001 --> 00:02:49,769
THE ANTI-FANS(?) AGREE

62
00:02:49,836 --> 00:02:51,838
SUCH A SUITABLE TRANSLATION

63
00:02:51,905 --> 00:02:54,140
In that aspect, Chef Hyun-suk would be

64
00:02:54,207 --> 00:02:56,709
-the old vibes guy.
-The old vibes.

65
00:02:56,776 --> 00:02:59,913
-Poong would be the crazy vibes guy.
-Crazy vibes.

66
00:02:59,979 --> 00:03:01,314
I'M THE DANCING VIBES GUY…

67
00:03:01,381 --> 00:03:04,617
-Our chefs are going global.
-They are.

68
00:03:04,684 --> 00:03:07,654
It's time to welcome
today's fridge owners.

69
00:03:07,720 --> 00:03:12,392
We can say that
these guests come with good vibes.

70
00:03:12,458 --> 00:03:16,996
I wonder who they are.
Let us present today's guests.

71
00:03:17,063 --> 00:03:18,631
Come on out!

72
00:03:18,698 --> 00:03:20,533
WE PRESENT THEM RIGHT NOW

73
00:03:20,600 --> 00:03:22,502
The fridge owners.

74
00:03:22,569 --> 00:03:26,139
Please welcome
Doh Kyung-soo and Park Byung-eun!

75
00:03:26,206 --> 00:03:28,942
Come on out. Hello.

76
00:03:29,008 --> 00:03:30,276
Come on out.

77
00:03:30,343 --> 00:03:32,645
Wait, you brought something with you.

78
00:03:32,712 --> 00:03:34,914
Yes, in the morning,

79
00:03:34,981 --> 00:03:36,816
-I went to the fish market.
-What?

80
00:03:36,883 --> 00:03:39,018
-You went there yourself?
-You went this morning?

81
00:03:39,085 --> 00:03:42,989
Why don't you leave those right here
and show us later?

82
00:03:43,056 --> 00:03:45,091
-He got those himself this morning?
-Wait a minute.

83
00:03:45,158 --> 00:03:47,260
-Please take your seat.
-Sure.

84
00:03:47,327 --> 00:03:49,662
Are you two acquainted?

85
00:03:49,729 --> 00:03:50,697
Yes, we are.

86
00:03:50,763 --> 00:03:54,567
<i>We lived together while working</i>
<i>on the same film for a couple of months,</i>

87
00:03:54,634 --> 00:03:57,670
-so we became quite close.
-I would think so.

88
00:03:57,737 --> 00:04:01,474
There's another reason
why we invited them together.

89
00:04:01,541 --> 00:04:03,543
They're the type of people

90
00:04:03,610 --> 00:04:07,280
who like to have fun with their hobbies
like they were professionals.

91
00:04:07,347 --> 00:04:09,482
He's as good as a professional cook,

92
00:04:09,549 --> 00:04:11,884
and he's as good
as a professional fisherman.

93
00:04:11,951 --> 00:04:15,955
Kyung-soo is even nicknamed D.O.ok.

94
00:04:16,022 --> 00:04:18,691
His stage name, D.O. plus cook.

95
00:04:18,758 --> 00:04:21,094
He's also known as a huge fan of the show.

96
00:04:21,160 --> 00:04:25,798
For a long time, he's mentioned his love
for <i>Chef & My Fridge</i> in many interviews.

97
00:04:25,865 --> 00:04:27,600
<i>In his 2016 interview,</i>

98
00:04:27,667 --> 00:04:30,637
<i>it says it's his wish</i>
<i>to be on</i> Chef & My Fridge.

99
00:04:30,703 --> 00:04:32,605
<i>And in his 2018 interview,</i>

100
00:04:32,672 --> 00:04:35,475
<i>he said he couldn't come</i>
<i>because he didn't have a fridge at home.</i>

101
00:04:35,541 --> 00:04:37,176
<i>He mentioned us again this year.</i>

102
00:04:37,243 --> 00:04:40,346
You said in an interview in January
that you wanted to be on the show.

103
00:04:40,413 --> 00:04:41,948
I really wanted to be here

104
00:04:42,015 --> 00:04:43,216
for a very long time.

105
00:04:43,283 --> 00:04:46,185
-You got your wish after nine years.
-Yes.

106
00:04:46,252 --> 00:04:50,089
-Have you been watching the new season?
-I watched everything,

107
00:04:50,156 --> 00:04:53,026
-even last week's episode.
-Really?

108
00:04:53,092 --> 00:04:55,695
Then you must find our chefs familiar.

109
00:04:55,762 --> 00:04:59,699
Very much. All of them.
I've known them for a long time.

110
00:04:59,766 --> 00:05:01,768
-Chef Jong-won is my recent favorite.
-Jong-won.

111
00:05:01,834 --> 00:05:04,570
-I knew it. He's the rising star.
-Yes.

112
00:05:04,637 --> 00:05:06,539
I saw that

113
00:05:06,606 --> 00:05:10,209
he always kept everything clean
whenever he cooked.

114
00:05:10,276 --> 00:05:11,277
<i>He cleans up.</i>

115
00:05:11,344 --> 00:05:13,279
I love it when chefs do that.

116
00:05:13,346 --> 00:05:14,580
You must like things neat and tidy.

117
00:05:14,647 --> 00:05:16,783
-Do you also clean as you cook?
-Yes.

118
00:05:17,850 --> 00:05:21,187
On the other hand,
people who cook like Poong

119
00:05:21,254 --> 00:05:22,221
must make you irritated.

120
00:05:22,288 --> 00:05:24,023
I wouldn't say he irritates me.

121
00:05:24,090 --> 00:05:27,393
-Does it bother you?
-I want to clean it up for him.

122
00:05:27,460 --> 00:05:29,028
Can you do that for me today?

123
00:05:29,095 --> 00:05:30,997
-Today?
-Yes, when I cook.

124
00:05:31,064 --> 00:05:32,699
-You said you would.
-He'll clean for you.

125
00:05:32,765 --> 00:05:34,133
This is why

126
00:05:34,200 --> 00:05:36,536
we should only have chefs on the show.

127
00:05:37,704 --> 00:05:39,772
-There's a loach among us.
-There is.

128
00:05:39,839 --> 00:05:41,607
Since when did you enjoy cooking?

129
00:05:41,674 --> 00:05:43,509
Around 2018.

130
00:05:44,243 --> 00:05:45,812
I began to enjoy doing it

131
00:05:45,878 --> 00:05:47,580
after I dined at a restaurant.

132
00:05:47,647 --> 00:05:50,316
-I tried a dish called bagna càuda,
-Bagna càuda?

133
00:05:50,383 --> 00:05:53,953
and the flavor of that dish
came as a huge shock to me.

134
00:05:54,020 --> 00:05:55,755
How did the chef create this flavor?

135
00:05:55,822 --> 00:05:58,124
-I began to get curious.
-I see.

136
00:05:58,191 --> 00:05:59,992
So I tried making the sauce at home

137
00:06:00,059 --> 00:06:01,694
and began to enjoy cooking altogether.

138
00:06:01,761 --> 00:06:04,997
Was that why you got
the cook license in Korean cuisine?

139
00:06:05,064 --> 00:06:08,835
-And you took the exam with your mother?
-Yes.

140
00:06:08,901 --> 00:06:11,904
Sons rarely do something like that,

141
00:06:11,971 --> 00:06:14,941
-spending time with their mothers.
-He's right.

142
00:06:15,007 --> 00:06:16,342
-He's a good son.
-I wanted to do that

143
00:06:16,409 --> 00:06:18,845
and make good memories,
so we took a class together

144
00:06:18,911 --> 00:06:20,747
to prepare for the exam.

145
00:06:20,813 --> 00:06:24,117
We have pictures of his efforts
in trying to obtain the license.

146
00:06:24,183 --> 00:06:25,284
Show us the proof.

147
00:06:25,351 --> 00:06:27,820
THIS IS HOW GOOD OF A COOK HE IS

148
00:06:27,887 --> 00:06:30,089
-You made all this?
-Yes.

149
00:06:30,156 --> 00:06:31,424
LIKE A LUXURY KOREAN RESTAURANT

150
00:06:31,491 --> 00:06:32,925
Everything looks so neat.

151
00:06:32,992 --> 00:06:36,129
It's not easy to make <i>tteok-guk</i>
with dumplings in just 50 minutes.

152
00:06:36,195 --> 00:06:39,265
-They look amazing.
-I've seen these dishes in restaurants.

153
00:06:39,332 --> 00:06:42,235
-Look at that little touch on the eggs.
-The steamed eggs?

154
00:06:42,301 --> 00:06:43,703
He made a flower.

155
00:06:43,770 --> 00:06:47,306
I took a class,
so the instructor taught me everything.

156
00:06:47,373 --> 00:06:49,308
When the production crew
asked you for the photos,

157
00:06:49,375 --> 00:06:51,377
you said, "Goodness, no."

158
00:06:51,444 --> 00:06:52,945
Then he sent all those.

159
00:06:53,012 --> 00:06:56,516
-I think he wanted to show them.
-I'd want to show them off.

160
00:06:56,582 --> 00:06:58,818
Most people would send just a couple.

161
00:06:58,885 --> 00:07:02,188
The crew member was surprised to see
so many photos come in.

162
00:07:02,255 --> 00:07:05,024
-They asked me for those, so…
-Exactly.

163
00:07:05,091 --> 00:07:07,960
Anyway, he's a really good cook.

164
00:07:08,027 --> 00:07:11,531
Another reason why he got licensed was

165
00:07:11,597 --> 00:07:13,933
because he wanted to serve
as a military cook.

166
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:16,936
I had to do my mandatory service anyway,
so I wanted to be the cook.

167
00:07:17,003 --> 00:07:18,805
FORMER MILITARY COOK 1

168
00:07:18,871 --> 00:07:22,241
-A military cook.
-And I had to have a license to apply.

169
00:07:22,308 --> 00:07:23,342
-Yes.
-That was why.

170
00:07:23,409 --> 00:07:27,146
He became the first idol star
to serve as a military cook.

171
00:07:27,213 --> 00:07:29,415
-He's set the record.
-He did?

172
00:07:29,482 --> 00:07:34,754
We basically make 180 servings or so
among 4 cooks.

173
00:07:34,821 --> 00:07:38,157
When we didn't have enough people,
three or even two of us would do it.

174
00:07:38,224 --> 00:07:40,126
Two people cooked that much food?

175
00:07:40,193 --> 00:07:42,562
Sung-jun, how much have you cooked?

176
00:07:42,628 --> 00:07:45,798
-We had two cooks.
-Two?

177
00:07:45,865 --> 00:07:47,300
We made 150 servings between us.

178
00:07:47,366 --> 00:07:49,068
-The 2 of you cooked for 150?
-Yes.

179
00:07:49,135 --> 00:07:50,937
-Is that possible?
-And three meals a day.

180
00:07:51,003 --> 00:07:54,207
-Nam-no was a military cook too.
-He was?

181
00:07:54,273 --> 00:07:56,542
I was on a different level
compared to them.

182
00:07:56,609 --> 00:07:58,611
-What? On a different level?
-As a military cook?

183
00:07:58,678 --> 00:08:00,847
-Did you cook for commissioned officers?
-There's a difference?

184
00:08:00,913 --> 00:08:02,381
-For commissioned officers?
-No way.

185
00:08:02,448 --> 00:08:04,851
I was deployed to Lebanon.

186
00:08:04,917 --> 00:08:07,453
I was there as the peacekeeping force,

187
00:08:07,520 --> 00:08:09,655
-and the acceptance rate was 200 to 1.
-I see.

188
00:08:09,722 --> 00:08:13,359
We had to cook for about 380 people,

189
00:08:13,426 --> 00:08:17,530
and they all ate 2 servings each,
so we had to make about 700 servings.

190
00:08:17,597 --> 00:08:22,068
After you served your time,
I thought you'd be sick of cooking.

191
00:08:22,134 --> 00:08:23,402
-Did you regret it?
-Did you?

192
00:08:23,469 --> 00:08:25,271
That's why I stopped cooking now.

193
00:08:25,338 --> 00:08:28,307
-See? I knew it.
-This isn't good.

194
00:08:28,374 --> 00:08:29,976
-D.O.ok, D.O. the cook.
-D.O.ok.

195
00:08:30,042 --> 00:08:34,947
There's a reason
why Kyung-soo came at this time.

196
00:08:35,014 --> 00:08:38,451
I'm releasing my first full album.

197
00:08:38,518 --> 00:08:42,054
I've never bleached my hair
in this color before.

198
00:08:42,989 --> 00:08:45,258
<i>It'll drop on July 7th.</i>

199
00:08:45,324 --> 00:08:48,828
<i>It's a fun and refreshing summer bop,</i>

200
00:08:48,895 --> 00:08:51,197
-so I decided to do this to my hair.
-I see.

201
00:08:51,264 --> 00:08:52,798
Your ears are quite red.

202
00:08:52,865 --> 00:08:56,235
My heart is racing really fast right now.

203
00:08:56,302 --> 00:08:57,436
HOW ENDEARING!

204
00:08:57,503 --> 00:08:59,805
Your ears can practically be picked off.

205
00:08:59,872 --> 00:09:01,474
-I'm fine.
-Are you okay?

206
00:09:01,541 --> 00:09:03,976
Byung-eun, is there anything
you need to promote too?

207
00:09:04,043 --> 00:09:05,845
HERE'S YOUR CHANCE

208
00:09:05,912 --> 00:09:07,246
-Anything is fine.
-Anything.

209
00:09:07,313 --> 00:09:09,582
-We'll give you a fair chance.
-Sing something.

210
00:09:09,649 --> 00:09:13,119
It doesn't have to be a song.
If you have upcoming project, tell us.

211
00:09:13,185 --> 00:09:15,488
<i>Kyung-soo is releasing his album</i>

212
00:09:15,555 --> 00:09:16,455
<i>On July 7th</i>

213
00:09:16,522 --> 00:09:19,458
<i>And it's my birthday in July</i>

214
00:09:21,294 --> 00:09:24,230
-Your birthday is in July?
-It's in July?

215
00:09:24,297 --> 00:09:25,331
On what day?

216
00:09:25,398 --> 00:09:27,066
-It's mid-July.
-Mid-July.

217
00:09:27,133 --> 00:09:28,734
-Congratulations.
-Congrats.

218
00:09:28,801 --> 00:09:31,137
Are my ears red too?

219
00:09:31,203 --> 00:09:35,107
I'm sorry to say that
you look flushed all over.

220
00:09:35,174 --> 00:09:37,376
-All right. D.O., the cook.
-D.O., the cook.

221
00:09:37,443 --> 00:09:39,412
Let's find out what Kyung-soo has

222
00:09:39,478 --> 00:09:43,049
by going through his fridge right now.

223
00:09:43,115 --> 00:09:45,351
Before we open it up,

224
00:09:45,418 --> 00:09:47,053
something happened for the first time.

225
00:09:47,119 --> 00:09:49,989
-He came out with a handcart.
-It's huge.

226
00:09:50,056 --> 00:09:52,992
I'm not the type
who keeps food sitting in the fridge.

227
00:09:53,059 --> 00:09:56,729
I like to buy ingredients
just before I cook.

228
00:09:56,796 --> 00:09:58,698
-You must want fresh food.
-I see.

229
00:09:58,764 --> 00:10:01,067
-You have to know what's really fresh.
-Yes.

230
00:10:01,133 --> 00:10:03,469
I usually just ask the merchant.

231
00:10:03,536 --> 00:10:07,073
Do you keep an eye on the store owner
and ask for their opinion?

232
00:10:07,139 --> 00:10:08,608
-And that's how you got these?
-Yes.

233
00:10:08,674 --> 00:10:10,109
Hello, everyone.

234
00:10:10,176 --> 00:10:12,445
I'm at Noryangjin Fish Market.

235
00:10:12,511 --> 00:10:14,847
How is this horse mackerel so big, sir?

236
00:10:14,914 --> 00:10:17,249
-It's a white trevally.
-I see.

237
00:10:17,316 --> 00:10:19,952
How long have you run this business?

238
00:10:20,019 --> 00:10:23,022
-Thirty years.
-Thirty years? Whoa.

239
00:10:23,089 --> 00:10:25,091
I'll take all these.

240
00:10:25,157 --> 00:10:27,893
And I'll take four of those too.

241
00:10:27,960 --> 00:10:29,161
-These?
-Yes.

242
00:10:29,228 --> 00:10:31,130
I bought some fish in season

243
00:10:31,197 --> 00:10:35,034
and other personal favorites.

244
00:10:35,101 --> 00:10:37,403
<i>-You got these this morning?</i>
<i>-Yes, just before the shoot.</i>

245
00:10:37,470 --> 00:10:38,704
Here's another thing.

246
00:10:38,771 --> 00:10:41,340
I didn't get anything
that might be in Byung-eun's fridge.

247
00:10:41,407 --> 00:10:43,843
CAREFULLY AVOIDING
THE SAME KIND OF INGREDIENTS

248
00:10:43,909 --> 00:10:45,678
Because he'll have lots of seafood.

249
00:10:45,745 --> 00:10:47,113
-He's an avid fisher.
-He is.

250
00:10:47,179 --> 00:10:49,048
You shouldn't have bought sea breams.

251
00:10:49,115 --> 00:10:50,750
-I didn't.
-No, right?

252
00:10:50,816 --> 00:10:52,918
He brought two boxes.
Let's open them up together.

253
00:10:52,985 --> 00:10:54,253
One, two, three.

254
00:10:54,320 --> 00:10:56,489
FULL BOXES

255
00:10:56,555 --> 00:10:58,090
-What does he have?
-What are those?

256
00:10:58,157 --> 00:11:00,893
First of all, this side.

257
00:11:00,960 --> 00:11:02,461
He got Venus clams.

258
00:11:02,528 --> 00:11:04,830
-Horned turbans.
-These. Horned turbans.

259
00:11:04,897 --> 00:11:06,732
-Venus clams, horned turbans.
-Horned turbans.

260
00:11:06,799 --> 00:11:08,334
-They look good.
-What's this?

261
00:11:08,401 --> 00:11:10,269
-Scallops.
-Pen shells?

262
00:11:10,336 --> 00:11:13,105
-Pen shells? Scallops? Just the meat.
-Scallops.

263
00:11:13,172 --> 00:11:14,940
Look at all those scallops.

264
00:11:15,007 --> 00:11:16,742
-Scallops.
-He got these in the morning.

265
00:11:16,809 --> 00:11:19,578
-What is this? A mummy or what?
-What is it?

266
00:11:19,645 --> 00:11:20,913
It's packed tightly.

267
00:11:20,980 --> 00:11:23,282
What is this?

268
00:11:23,349 --> 00:11:24,817
You'll see it now.

269
00:11:24,884 --> 00:11:27,987
Yes, there it is.

270
00:11:28,554 --> 00:11:30,256
WHAT'S THIS SHINY FISH?

271
00:11:30,322 --> 00:11:31,657
It looks so pretty.

272
00:11:31,724 --> 00:11:32,958
-Threeline grunt.
-Threeline grunt.

273
00:11:33,025 --> 00:11:35,795
I had the guts removed.

274
00:11:35,861 --> 00:11:38,397
-So that's what it looks like?
-Yes.

275
00:11:38,464 --> 00:11:40,066
Let's take a look at this box.

276
00:11:40,132 --> 00:11:41,167
Is this squid?

277
00:11:41,233 --> 00:11:43,469
-Yes, I got squid too.
-Squid.

278
00:11:43,536 --> 00:11:46,405
What about these? Stalked sea squirt.

279
00:11:46,472 --> 00:11:48,641
Stalked sea squirt.

280
00:11:48,708 --> 00:11:50,910
-You got all your favorites, right?
-Yes.

281
00:11:50,976 --> 00:11:52,411
He got these because he likes them.

282
00:11:52,478 --> 00:11:54,180
What's this?

283
00:11:54,246 --> 00:11:56,115
-It's a fish.
-Blackthroat seaperch.

284
00:11:56,182 --> 00:11:59,085
-It looks so fresh.
-It's fatty and in season now.

285
00:11:59,151 --> 00:12:00,720
-It's expensive.
-Blackthroat seaperch.

286
00:12:00,786 --> 00:12:03,322
Did you think he wouldn't have this?

287
00:12:03,389 --> 00:12:05,324
-No.
-Have you never caught this?

288
00:12:05,391 --> 00:12:06,992
I've caught it before.

289
00:12:07,059 --> 00:12:08,027
-You have?
-Yes.

290
00:12:08,094 --> 00:12:10,529
-I catch all kinds of fish.
-In that case,

291
00:12:10,596 --> 00:12:12,531
what was the rarest one you caught?

292
00:12:12,598 --> 00:12:15,301
-A shark.
-A shark?

293
00:12:15,367 --> 00:12:16,869
-A shark?
-You've caught a shark?

294
00:12:16,936 --> 00:12:19,371
-You've caught a shark?
-It was over two meters long.

295
00:12:20,239 --> 00:12:23,042
-That sounds fake.
-Two meters? That's bigger than a person.

296
00:12:23,109 --> 00:12:25,878
<i>It sounds like</i> The Old Man and the Sea.

297
00:12:25,945 --> 00:12:28,013
<i>I caught a sea bream about this big.</i>

298
00:12:28,080 --> 00:12:30,382
But the reel kept rolling out.

299
00:12:30,449 --> 00:12:33,786
That shark had bitten
the sea bream I just caught.

300
00:12:33,853 --> 00:12:35,421
I didn't know that was possible.

301
00:12:35,488 --> 00:12:36,989
He's a guy who has caught a shark.

302
00:12:37,056 --> 00:12:40,593
But Kyung-soo thought
he wouldn't have blackthroat seaperch.

303
00:12:40,659 --> 00:12:44,096
-He thought it was hard to catch.
-Maybe he has shark meat.

304
00:12:44,163 --> 00:12:48,167
All right, now. He's serious about food,
so he got all these from a fish market.

305
00:12:48,234 --> 00:12:50,102
Does he keep red meat here, then?

306
00:12:50,169 --> 00:12:52,638
-Probably.
-He has seafood here.

307
00:12:52,705 --> 00:12:56,008
-We present Kyung-soo's fridge!
-Kyung-soo's fridge!

308
00:12:56,075 --> 00:12:57,376
Tudum.

309
00:12:57,443 --> 00:12:59,545
-Tudum.
-What?

310
00:12:59,612 --> 00:13:02,581
-We present Kyung-soo's fridge!
-Kyung-soo's fridge!

311
00:13:02,648 --> 00:13:04,116
Tudum.

312
00:13:04,183 --> 00:13:05,384
-Tudum.
-What?

313
00:13:05,451 --> 00:13:07,052
-It's empty.
-It's empty.

314
00:13:07,119 --> 00:13:10,156
The top shelf is completely empty.

315
00:13:10,723 --> 00:13:12,258
All he has is ginger <i>cheong</i>.

316
00:13:12,324 --> 00:13:14,393
You can put this up for lease.

317
00:13:14,460 --> 00:13:16,328
What's going on here?

318
00:13:16,395 --> 00:13:19,999
You don't seem to have
too many ingredients inside.

319
00:13:20,065 --> 00:13:23,035
I don't like to keep food
piled up in the fridge,

320
00:13:23,102 --> 00:13:24,170
so I throw everything away.

321
00:13:24,236 --> 00:13:27,206
-Do you shop for groceries as needed?
-Yes.

322
00:13:27,273 --> 00:13:30,342
Let's see. He has a side dish.
Are these stir-fried anchovies?

323
00:13:30,409 --> 00:13:33,345
My mother made that.

324
00:13:33,412 --> 00:13:36,549
And that one is
probably pickled artichokes.

325
00:13:36,615 --> 00:13:39,919
I went to this restaurant,
and that side dish was really good,

326
00:13:39,985 --> 00:13:42,688
and it was available for sale.

327
00:13:42,755 --> 00:13:43,989
So I got that.

328
00:13:44,056 --> 00:13:46,125
-I see.
-Pickled artichokes.

329
00:13:46,192 --> 00:13:47,860
This must be chicken.

330
00:13:47,927 --> 00:13:51,630
Don't people usually buy
prepared chicken parts?

331
00:13:51,697 --> 00:13:54,466
I like to cook a whole chicken

332
00:13:54,533 --> 00:13:58,070
inside a pressure cooker like <i>samgyetang,</i>
chicken soup with ginseng.

333
00:13:58,137 --> 00:13:59,972
Like <i>baeksuk</i>, chicken soup.

334
00:14:00,039 --> 00:14:01,707
-That way, it's delicious.
-It is.

335
00:14:01,774 --> 00:14:03,475
And some vegetables.

336
00:14:03,542 --> 00:14:05,277
Green onions. Are these chives?

337
00:14:05,344 --> 00:14:08,414
But unlike other people,
his vegetables come with dirt.

338
00:14:08,480 --> 00:14:10,583
I think these are more delicious.

339
00:14:10,649 --> 00:14:12,418
-More than the cleaned ones?
-Yes.

340
00:14:12,484 --> 00:14:15,020
Isn't it fresher with dirt?

341
00:14:15,087 --> 00:14:17,089
-Mostly, yes.
-It's better than putting it in water.

342
00:14:17,156 --> 00:14:18,457
It'll have a stronger smell.

343
00:14:18,524 --> 00:14:20,960
He's serious about cooking.

344
00:14:21,026 --> 00:14:22,761
I see lots of vegetables.

345
00:14:22,828 --> 00:14:24,096
Apple mint.

346
00:14:24,163 --> 00:14:25,130
Perilla leaves.

347
00:14:25,197 --> 00:14:26,999
Carrots, cucumbers, and a radish.

348
00:14:27,066 --> 00:14:29,068
-I like veggies.
-You do?

349
00:14:29,134 --> 00:14:31,070
I like to eat them raw too.

350
00:14:31,136 --> 00:14:32,338
How do you season them?

351
00:14:32,404 --> 00:14:35,407
Salt, sesame oil, and maybe olive oil.

352
00:14:35,474 --> 00:14:37,643
-I just like to eat it fresh.
-I see.

353
00:14:38,244 --> 00:14:40,412
I see some nectarines. Do you like these?

354
00:14:40,479 --> 00:14:42,414
-They're in season now.
-They are.

355
00:14:42,481 --> 00:14:43,716
Where do you get your nectarines?

356
00:14:43,782 --> 00:14:47,653
I go to a fruit stand
in the local marketplace.

357
00:14:47,720 --> 00:14:50,656
-I only get my fruit from there.
-We all have that one place.

358
00:14:50,723 --> 00:14:55,194
The fruit stand in that marketplace
always has the best fruit,

359
00:14:55,261 --> 00:14:57,062
-so I only buy from them.
-Only from them.

360
00:14:57,129 --> 00:14:59,431
Lemons. How do you use cherry tomatoes?

361
00:14:59,498 --> 00:15:01,634
-I use them for pasta.
-Pasta, of course.

362
00:15:01,700 --> 00:15:04,203
-Also, some sauces.
-To the side shelves.

363
00:15:04,270 --> 00:15:05,204
He has lots of sauces.

364
00:15:05,271 --> 00:15:06,171
He does.

365
00:15:06,238 --> 00:15:09,041
I thought we'd have more to see.

366
00:15:09,108 --> 00:15:11,677
What's this?
It's sitting alone in the freezer.

367
00:15:11,744 --> 00:15:13,579
-I think it's whiskey.
-Yes, it's whiskey.

368
00:15:13,646 --> 00:15:16,048
I like to make very chilled high ball.

369
00:15:16,115 --> 00:15:17,583
That's why you had all those lemons.

370
00:15:17,650 --> 00:15:20,819
Did you know it's even more delicious
when it's kept in the freezer?

371
00:15:20,886 --> 00:15:22,788
-Yes.
-It becomes thicker too.

372
00:15:22,855 --> 00:15:26,058
-I don't see any meat.
-No, there is a pack.

373
00:15:26,125 --> 00:15:27,126
We finally found one.

374
00:15:27,192 --> 00:15:29,728
-Pork belly. Do you like this?
-I do.

375
00:15:29,795 --> 00:15:31,130
Do you prefer pork to beef?

376
00:15:31,196 --> 00:15:33,899
I prefer lamb, pork, chicken,
and beef, in that order.

377
00:15:33,966 --> 00:15:35,567
-Lamb, pork, chicken, and beef.
-He likes lamb.

378
00:15:35,634 --> 00:15:37,870
-Lamb.
-You like lamb?

379
00:15:37,937 --> 00:15:39,471
A guy who's serious about cooking

380
00:15:39,538 --> 00:15:42,541
that was Kyung-soo's fridge!

381
00:15:43,375 --> 00:15:45,878
-I'm glad he brought these.
-Me too.

382
00:15:45,945 --> 00:15:47,546
That's why he went shopping.

383
00:15:47,613 --> 00:15:50,082
He wanted to be here

384
00:15:50,149 --> 00:15:52,618
with his fridge since 2016.

385
00:15:52,685 --> 00:15:56,655
I wonder what he'll order today.

386
00:15:56,722 --> 00:15:58,457
Let's find out his orders.

387
00:15:58,524 --> 00:16:01,193
-The first one is called cold baby.
-Cold baby?

388
00:16:01,260 --> 00:16:03,228
-Why is it cold baby?
-Is that a song title?

389
00:16:03,295 --> 00:16:05,698
-There's "Call Me Baby" by EXO.
-"Call Me Baby."

390
00:16:06,699 --> 00:16:11,770
This is because I wanted to try
a delicious cold dish.

391
00:16:11,837 --> 00:16:12,938
Since it's summer.

392
00:16:13,005 --> 00:16:16,976
There are cold dishes
like <i>naengmyeon </i>and buckwheat noodles.

393
00:16:17,042 --> 00:16:18,610
But nothing like those.

394
00:16:18,677 --> 00:16:23,082
I want to try a cold dish
that I've never had before,

395
00:16:23,148 --> 00:16:25,284
but something still delicious.

396
00:16:25,351 --> 00:16:28,220
I want to ask you
to make something like that.

397
00:16:28,921 --> 00:16:31,023
-What's the next order?
-A cold dish.

398
00:16:31,090 --> 00:16:33,993
-There it is.
-D.O.ryangjin Fish Market.

399
00:16:34,059 --> 00:16:36,495
This is why he went shopping this morning.

400
00:16:36,562 --> 00:16:39,732
I really love seafood

401
00:16:39,798 --> 00:16:43,068
so I want to ask you
to use everything I got today.

402
00:16:43,135 --> 00:16:44,403
Without leaving anything.

403
00:16:44,470 --> 00:16:46,872
And because he was a military cook,
I think the other two

404
00:16:46,939 --> 00:16:50,743
-should take this as ex-military cooks.
-They should.

405
00:16:50,809 --> 00:16:52,144
In that case, I'll take it first.

406
00:16:52,211 --> 00:16:53,946
Sung-jun raises his hand.

407
00:16:54,013 --> 00:16:56,081
Not only was I a military cook,

408
00:16:56,148 --> 00:16:58,250
but I love seafood more than meat.

409
00:16:58,317 --> 00:17:01,487
-I'll take the fish market.
-The fish market.

410
00:17:01,553 --> 00:17:03,355
-I'll take one.
-There he is.

411
00:17:03,422 --> 00:17:07,259
-Formerly deployed to Lebanon, right?
-A military cook overseas.

412
00:17:07,326 --> 00:17:09,028
I'll take D.O.ryangjin Fish Market.

413
00:17:09,094 --> 00:17:10,963
-Hey.
-They're both working with seafood.

414
00:17:11,030 --> 00:17:14,033
We both may have been military cooks,
but I'll show you I'm on another level.

415
00:17:15,067 --> 00:17:17,102
He's taking that order.

416
00:17:17,169 --> 00:17:18,871
The two military cooks are up.

417
00:17:18,937 --> 00:17:21,974
And now, no one has taken up cold baby.

418
00:17:22,040 --> 00:17:23,842
-What?
-I'll go.

419
00:17:23,909 --> 00:17:26,211
-What? Jong-won.
-I'll go.

420
00:17:26,278 --> 00:17:28,147
Okay. Ready, sing.

421
00:17:28,781 --> 00:17:31,850
-You can't do this for free.
-You have to sing.

422
00:17:31,917 --> 00:17:34,453
All right. You said you'd take it.

423
00:17:34,520 --> 00:17:35,854
Okay, Jong-won.

424
00:17:35,921 --> 00:17:37,523
THE BIGGEST CRISIS SINCE THE SHOW BEGAN

425
00:17:37,589 --> 00:17:38,724
PEOPLE ARE GETTING PUMPED UP

426
00:17:39,324 --> 00:17:40,893
Time to go, Jong-won.

427
00:17:40,959 --> 00:17:42,761
THE SHY VIBES GUY…

428
00:17:42,828 --> 00:17:45,397
-Look at our manager right now.
-He's ready.

429
00:17:45,464 --> 00:17:47,332
I'm going home.

430
00:17:47,399 --> 00:17:49,501
-Goodness, sir, no.
-Don't go.

431
00:17:49,568 --> 00:17:51,370
I'm so sorry, sir.

432
00:17:51,437 --> 00:17:53,038
-Okay.
-I'm sorry.

433
00:17:54,239 --> 00:17:57,076
Our manager isn't that easy.

434
00:17:57,142 --> 00:17:59,078
-One, two, three, four.
-Please do it with me.

435
00:17:59,645 --> 00:18:02,181
TIMIDLY REVS UP "COLD BABY"

436
00:18:02,247 --> 00:18:03,282
JONG-WON PICKS COLD BABY

437
00:18:03,348 --> 00:18:05,417
And next? Who's that?

438
00:18:05,484 --> 00:18:06,952
-You'll take it?
-I will.

439
00:18:07,719 --> 00:18:09,455
-The world star. Nice.
-First of all,

440
00:18:09,521 --> 00:18:12,291
just as Kyung-soo mentioned before,

441
00:18:12,357 --> 00:18:14,660
he wanted a dish that doesn't exist.

442
00:18:15,227 --> 00:18:16,795
I DID?

443
00:18:16,862 --> 00:18:19,932
-I really want to try doing that.
-He's the expert at that.

444
00:18:19,998 --> 00:18:21,934
I only make dishes that don't exist.

445
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:23,735
Be careful what you wish for.

446
00:18:23,802 --> 00:18:26,171
-Really?
-It sounds like so much fun.

447
00:18:26,238 --> 00:18:28,807
There must be a reason
why it doesn't exist in this world.

448
00:18:28,874 --> 00:18:30,809
-But Poong takes the slot.
-I will.

449
00:18:30,876 --> 00:18:32,644
-Poong took it.
-I'm looking forward to it.

450
00:18:32,711 --> 00:18:34,646
Jong-won versus Poong.

451
00:18:34,713 --> 00:18:36,381
Let's begin the 15-minute cook-offs!

452
00:18:40,352 --> 00:18:45,023
<i>This is the first round</i>
<i>with ingredients from Kyung-soo's fridge.</i>

453
00:18:45,090 --> 00:18:47,426
You've all been waiting for this moment.

454
00:18:47,493 --> 00:18:48,727
The entire country,

455
00:18:48,794 --> 00:18:52,965
no, the entire world
has been waiting for this match.

456
00:18:53,031 --> 00:18:56,068
The two polar opposites
of <i>Chef & My Fridge.</i>

457
00:18:56,135 --> 00:18:59,037
A top chef who runs
a fine dining restaurant, Son Jong-won is

458
00:18:59,104 --> 00:19:03,408
up against the most chaotic cook,
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong.

459
00:19:03,475 --> 00:19:05,544
Let me share a few online comments.

460
00:19:05,611 --> 00:19:07,813
"Poong from the wild
suddenly appeared before the eyes

461
00:19:07,880 --> 00:19:09,982
of this sheltered man."

462
00:19:10,048 --> 00:19:13,352
"This is why
the male lead, an elite prince,

463
00:19:13,418 --> 00:19:16,889
always falls for the sassy
and chaotic female lead."

464
00:19:16,955 --> 00:19:18,857
THE SASSY FEMALE (?) LEAD TYPE

465
00:19:18,924 --> 00:19:20,726
-I see.
-This is awful.

466
00:19:20,792 --> 00:19:22,828
-This is awful.
-Was that a frilled lizard?

467
00:19:22,895 --> 00:19:25,197
-The sassy girl.
-The sassy girl's pigtails?

468
00:19:25,264 --> 00:19:29,301
When Chef Jong-won first joined us,

469
00:19:29,368 --> 00:19:32,971
his condition was that
he'd never fight Poong.

470
00:19:33,038 --> 00:19:34,039
I thought so.

471
00:19:34,106 --> 00:19:35,240
It hits hard.

472
00:19:35,307 --> 00:19:37,943
He once asked the production crew
to do that.

473
00:19:38,010 --> 00:19:39,845
I don't think it should be good,
but it is.

474
00:19:39,912 --> 00:19:42,080
Poong is just amazing.

475
00:19:42,147 --> 00:19:44,216
<i>He slowly fell for him,</i>

476
00:19:44,283 --> 00:19:47,186
<i>and he even shed tears</i>
<i>when Poong made a dish.</i>

477
00:19:47,252 --> 00:19:48,887
That's where we're at now.

478
00:19:48,954 --> 00:19:50,189
He was "Poong-a-fied."

479
00:19:50,255 --> 00:19:53,125
It looks like
he has such an unusual taste.

480
00:19:53,192 --> 00:19:56,461
But you must be confident
about your cooking skills.

481
00:19:57,029 --> 00:20:00,532
In my head, I do think
that it's only natural that I win.

482
00:20:00,599 --> 00:20:02,534
But I'm afraid at heart.

483
00:20:03,101 --> 00:20:04,937
-That's love.
-Your heart?

484
00:20:05,003 --> 00:20:06,738
-Is this love?
-It's love.

485
00:20:06,805 --> 00:20:10,409
Can Chef Jong-won handle this?

486
00:20:10,475 --> 00:20:11,810
-Handle what?
-Me.

487
00:20:11,877 --> 00:20:14,046
-You?
-Yes.

488
00:20:14,112 --> 00:20:15,781
PEEKS

489
00:20:15,847 --> 00:20:19,585
-I'm a chef, so I should do better.
-All right.

490
00:20:19,651 --> 00:20:20,886
He lost his spirit.

491
00:20:20,953 --> 00:20:22,688
Why does he seem so far from confident?

492
00:20:22,754 --> 00:20:24,056
I don't know why I feel so small.

493
00:20:24,122 --> 00:20:26,024
-It'll hit hard if you lose.
-Seriously.

494
00:20:26,091 --> 00:20:29,561
You can ride it out.
Someone here has lost to him three times.

495
00:20:30,128 --> 00:20:31,396
A CHEF SUFFERING FROM POONGPHOBIA

496
00:20:31,463 --> 00:20:33,232
Poongphobia is as scary as a panic attack.

497
00:20:33,298 --> 00:20:34,933
He lost all three times.

498
00:20:35,867 --> 00:20:37,836
CHEF JONG-WON'S INGREDIENTS: APPLE MINT,
WHITE BALSAMIC VINEGAR, BURRATA, ROMAINE

499
00:20:37,903 --> 00:20:39,938
BISCUITS, NECTARINES, ALMONDS,
STIR-FRIED ANCHOVIES, HONEY

500
00:20:40,005 --> 00:20:42,841
What are you making today, Chef Jong-won?

501
00:20:42,908 --> 00:20:45,177
The dish I prepared is called

502
00:20:45,244 --> 00:20:47,713
Honey NecD.O.rine.

503
00:20:47,779 --> 00:20:48,780
NecD.O.rine.

504
00:20:48,847 --> 00:20:51,516
-Honey NecD.O.rine.
-A cold nectarine dish?

505
00:20:51,583 --> 00:20:54,052
I'll grill nectarines
and serve them chilled.

506
00:20:54,119 --> 00:20:55,787
Grilled, and then chilled?

507
00:20:55,854 --> 00:21:00,125
Not only is it cold in temperature,
but he also had cold herbs like mint.

508
00:21:00,192 --> 00:21:03,095
So I'll use those
to prepare a refreshing summer dish.

509
00:21:03,161 --> 00:21:05,497
I also saw stir-fried anchovies.

510
00:21:05,564 --> 00:21:07,532
-Made by my mom.
-Yes, your mother's food.

511
00:21:07,599 --> 00:21:09,534
You also mentioned bagna càuda,

512
00:21:09,601 --> 00:21:11,670
and it's a dish that uses anchovies.

513
00:21:11,737 --> 00:21:13,939
So I'll use that Korean anchovy dish

514
00:21:14,006 --> 00:21:16,308
and turn them into crumbs.

515
00:21:16,375 --> 00:21:17,442
To make it crunchy?

516
00:21:17,509 --> 00:21:19,011
-What do I call that?
-Crunchiness?

517
00:21:19,077 --> 00:21:20,545
I'll add some crunchiness.

518
00:21:20,612 --> 00:21:23,048
He just asked Poong.

519
00:21:23,115 --> 00:21:24,383
Why did he ask me?

520
00:21:24,449 --> 00:21:27,953
-He relies a lot on Poong.
-He does.

521
00:21:28,020 --> 00:21:30,789
He could've asked
either Nam-no or Sung-jun,

522
00:21:30,856 --> 00:21:33,659
but he looked at Poong
when he was in trouble.

523
00:21:33,725 --> 00:21:36,194
He's relying on him now.

524
00:21:36,261 --> 00:21:38,730
-I already feel caught up in this.
-You have been.

525
00:21:39,665 --> 00:21:41,166
WEBTOON ARTIST POONG'S INGREDIENTS:
CHERRY TOMATO, CUCUMBER, SOY SAUCE, LEMON

526
00:21:41,233 --> 00:21:42,734
CHICKEN STOCK, CARROT, OYSTER SAUCE,
RADISH, SPRING ONION, HONEY, PERILLA LEAF

527
00:21:42,801 --> 00:21:46,505
The name of the dish I'm making is…

528
00:21:46,571 --> 00:21:47,773
WHAT IS IT?

529
00:21:47,839 --> 00:21:49,041
I'll make cold egg soup.

530
00:21:49,641 --> 00:21:50,575
Have you ever heard of it?

531
00:21:50,642 --> 00:21:52,144
Cold egg soup?

532
00:21:52,210 --> 00:21:54,012
-I don't want to hear it.
-He's crazy.

533
00:21:54,079 --> 00:21:55,714
We've never had cold egg soup.

534
00:21:55,781 --> 00:21:56,882
That sounds tough to handle.

535
00:21:56,948 --> 00:21:58,984
I'll fry some eggs

536
00:21:59,051 --> 00:22:01,586
and handle them in some way,

537
00:22:01,653 --> 00:22:03,221
-chill them, and…
-How will you handle them?

538
00:22:03,288 --> 00:22:05,657
-Handle them how?
-How are you going to do it?

539
00:22:05,724 --> 00:22:08,126
-It's not like you'll throw it away.
-Like food waste?

540
00:22:08,193 --> 00:22:10,362
-Do you have a secret?
-It'll jump between cold and hot.

541
00:22:10,429 --> 00:22:13,298
It'll jump between cold and hot water
to drain all its grease.

542
00:22:13,365 --> 00:22:16,335
That creates a texture
similar to fried tofu.

543
00:22:16,401 --> 00:22:21,306
When it's added to cold soup,
its buttery flavor will taste

544
00:22:21,373 --> 00:22:24,109
new and refreshing.

545
00:22:24,176 --> 00:22:27,145
Also, I'll make the soup
with vegetable stock.

546
00:22:27,212 --> 00:22:28,647
Poong is using vegetable stock?

547
00:22:28,714 --> 00:22:31,249
I'll use all kinds of vegetables,

548
00:22:31,316 --> 00:22:35,253
and I'll marinade some cherry tomatoes

549
00:22:35,320 --> 00:22:37,923
-for you to eat on the side.
-Marinade.

550
00:22:37,989 --> 00:22:40,158
-I'm looking forward to this.
-I see.

551
00:22:40,225 --> 00:22:45,030
And now, let us begin the round
to fill the cold baby order for Kyung-soo.

552
00:22:45,097 --> 00:22:46,264
Gosh.

553
00:22:46,965 --> 00:22:49,167
A man who is crazy about details.

554
00:22:49,234 --> 00:22:51,303
-A top chef in the fine dining industry.
-He already lost his spirit.

555
00:22:51,370 --> 00:22:53,238
Chef Jong-won is up.

556
00:22:53,305 --> 00:22:55,040
His opponent is just a crazy guy.

557
00:22:56,141 --> 00:22:57,909
The most chaotic cook,

558
00:22:57,976 --> 00:23:00,278
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong.

559
00:23:00,345 --> 00:23:03,949
Which one of them will capture
Kyung-soo's heart?

560
00:23:04,015 --> 00:23:07,185
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

561
00:23:09,254 --> 00:23:10,622
-The 15 minutes has begun.
-Good luck!

562
00:23:10,689 --> 00:23:12,290
Begin!

563
00:23:12,357 --> 00:23:14,259
THE MICHELIN-STAR CHEF
VS THE COOK OF THE DARK

564
00:23:14,326 --> 00:23:16,495
-The 15 minutes has begun.
-Good luck!

565
00:23:16,561 --> 00:23:20,766
Poong's less-than-perfect skills will
make him lower his expectations,

566
00:23:20,832 --> 00:23:23,635
but I think he'll make
a delicious dish as a twist.

567
00:23:23,702 --> 00:23:26,438
-Artist Poong is making vegetable stock.
-He is?

568
00:23:26,505 --> 00:23:29,040
-You're using lemon peel?
-Yes.

569
00:23:29,107 --> 00:23:30,275
1. MAKE VEGETABLE STOCK

570
00:23:30,342 --> 00:23:31,910
It must smell good.

571
00:23:31,977 --> 00:23:34,279
I've never seen him make
vegetable stock before.

572
00:23:34,346 --> 00:23:36,114
He had chicken stock and all.

573
00:23:36,181 --> 00:23:37,816
He didn't use that.

574
00:23:37,883 --> 00:23:39,918
The Ice Prince is up.

575
00:23:39,985 --> 00:23:41,820
Jong-won the good vibes guy.

576
00:23:43,355 --> 00:23:45,223
FLOUR, EGG WHITES

577
00:23:45,290 --> 00:23:47,993
Jong-won has exquisite details as always.

578
00:23:49,027 --> 00:23:50,262
MEASURING AND ADDING LOTS OF HONEY

579
00:23:50,328 --> 00:23:52,864
Chef Jong-won added egg whites, flour,

580
00:23:52,931 --> 00:23:54,566
and even honey.

581
00:23:54,633 --> 00:23:57,702
-I think that's the tuile batter.
-Tuile?

582
00:23:57,769 --> 00:24:00,505
Chef Jong-won's side
must be playing classical music,

583
00:24:00,572 --> 00:24:03,875
whereas Artist Poong's side
must be playing rock and roll.

584
00:24:05,143 --> 00:24:06,278
Red pepper powder.

585
00:24:06,344 --> 00:24:07,712
-He's making chili oil.
-As always.

586
00:24:07,779 --> 00:24:10,015
He always makes that, no matter what.

587
00:24:10,081 --> 00:24:12,551
Can't you just use store-bought chili oil?

588
00:24:12,617 --> 00:24:15,454
-No, it's better when it's made fresh.
-It's a must.

589
00:24:15,520 --> 00:24:18,190
We won't see him do much
unless he does that.

590
00:24:18,256 --> 00:24:19,491
GARLIC CLOVE DESTROYED

591
00:24:20,492 --> 00:24:21,827
He's very wild.

592
00:24:21,893 --> 00:24:22,861
GARLIC

593
00:24:24,329 --> 00:24:26,631
He never goes a week without making that.

594
00:24:26,698 --> 00:24:28,033
Poong's chili oil.

595
00:24:28,600 --> 00:24:30,635
RUBBING OLIVE OIL ON A HEATED PAN

596
00:24:30,702 --> 00:24:31,670
Whoa, the heat is high.

597
00:24:31,736 --> 00:24:33,171
Is he burning the pan?

598
00:24:33,238 --> 00:24:34,739
He heated it up.

599
00:24:34,806 --> 00:24:36,341
-It's on fire.
-That's a really high heat.

600
00:24:37,676 --> 00:24:38,910
Isn't the pan burnt?

601
00:24:38,977 --> 00:24:40,812
Wouldn't it smell a bit burnt?

602
00:24:40,879 --> 00:24:43,381
The ingredients would burn too quickly
if he puts it in there.

603
00:24:43,448 --> 00:24:45,183
-The heat is very high.
-Why did he do that?

604
00:24:45,250 --> 00:24:47,152
Did you set it on fire?
Or was it an accident?

605
00:24:47,719 --> 00:24:49,754
-It was an accident.
-Right?

606
00:24:50,322 --> 00:24:53,124
CHUCKLING(?)

607
00:24:53,191 --> 00:24:55,494
I realized this
when I just heard him say that.

608
00:24:55,560 --> 00:24:57,963
He's a guy who has everything,
including honesty.

609
00:24:59,064 --> 00:25:00,332
He didn't lie.

610
00:25:00,398 --> 00:25:02,801
He's spreading the batter
on a comb-shaped mold.

611
00:25:02,868 --> 00:25:04,469
There's a snack shaped like that.

612
00:25:04,536 --> 00:25:06,972
-But I didn't use sugar.
-It's to make that shape.

613
00:25:07,038 --> 00:25:10,942
I saw that he brought four bags
back in the green room.

614
00:25:11,009 --> 00:25:13,345
He had a lot of kitchen tools
like an all-inclusive bag.

615
00:25:13,411 --> 00:25:15,881
He didn't know what he'd make,
so he brought everything.

616
00:25:15,947 --> 00:25:18,750
It's just like how we bring our knives.

617
00:25:18,817 --> 00:25:21,353
-I only carry one knife.
-Right?

618
00:25:21,419 --> 00:25:25,056
-He's making a case for himself.
-I mean, four bags? Come on.

619
00:25:25,123 --> 00:25:28,026
But he can use his tools
to make a variety of dishes.

620
00:25:28,093 --> 00:25:29,194
SETTING THE TIMER

621
00:25:30,128 --> 00:25:32,130
Poong is using cherry tomatoes.

622
00:25:32,998 --> 00:25:34,299
Whoa, that's a lot of sugar.

623
00:25:34,366 --> 00:25:35,600
Did you pour sugar into tomatoes?

624
00:25:35,667 --> 00:25:39,104
-Yes, I'm trying to marinade them quickly.
-Marinading.

625
00:25:40,071 --> 00:25:42,974
The sugar needs to seep in quickly,
so I had to use a lot.

626
00:25:43,041 --> 00:25:44,676
Does the speed depend on the quantity?

627
00:25:44,743 --> 00:25:46,811
Not really, but it'll help a little.

628
00:25:46,878 --> 00:25:48,046
What's important is this.

629
00:25:48,113 --> 00:25:50,282
Tomato peels are just like plastic wraps.

630
00:25:50,348 --> 00:25:52,350
If he puts them in without peeling them,

631
00:25:52,417 --> 00:25:54,819
it won't get marinaded
even after ten years.

632
00:25:54,886 --> 00:25:57,756
That's why tomatoes are
always peeled first.

633
00:25:57,822 --> 00:25:59,124
It's like plastic wrap.

634
00:25:59,190 --> 00:26:01,059
Nothing gets through.

635
00:26:01,126 --> 00:26:02,928
CONDIMENT 2, CHICKEN STOCK

636
00:26:02,994 --> 00:26:04,529
That's why tomatoes are
always peeled first.

637
00:26:04,596 --> 00:26:06,765
Tomato peels can't even be digested.

638
00:26:06,831 --> 00:26:10,569
Poong just poured in
three condiments into the vegetable stock.

639
00:26:10,635 --> 00:26:12,804
-He did?
-Why did you use vegetables?

640
00:26:12,871 --> 00:26:13,972
It was a trap.

641
00:26:14,673 --> 00:26:17,409
-He pretended to make a healthy dish.
-He put in three condiments.

642
00:26:17,475 --> 00:26:20,612
If you were going to use those,
why did you use so many veggies?

643
00:26:20,679 --> 00:26:21,780
Condiments are delicious.

644
00:26:21,846 --> 00:26:23,882
How can vegetable stock
turn out so yellow?

645
00:26:23,949 --> 00:26:25,517
DELICIOUSLY COLORED IN GOLDEN YELLOW

646
00:26:25,584 --> 00:26:28,353
The veggies were really fresh.

647
00:26:28,420 --> 00:26:31,056
The owner hasn't noticed.

648
00:26:31,122 --> 00:26:34,059
No one would've known
if you hadn't mentioned it.

649
00:26:34,125 --> 00:26:36,928
-Why did he tell everyone?
-We almost missed it.

650
00:26:36,995 --> 00:26:38,930
-I saw everything.
-You did?

651
00:26:38,997 --> 00:26:42,334
-Right?
-It's D.O. the cook. He sees everything.

652
00:26:42,400 --> 00:26:45,537
But the vegetable stock he's boiling
looks so delicious even now.

653
00:26:45,604 --> 00:26:47,238
-Even now, right?
-It has to be good.

654
00:26:47,305 --> 00:26:50,408
One of them is honest,
and the other one is pulling tricks.

655
00:26:50,475 --> 00:26:53,178
-There's a contrast.
-There is.

656
00:26:53,244 --> 00:26:54,512
MAKING CUTS IN A NECTARINE

657
00:26:57,148 --> 00:26:59,417
AND HE TWISTS IT RIGHT AWAY

658
00:27:01,720 --> 00:27:03,455
He gets the nectarines ready.

659
00:27:04,656 --> 00:27:07,092
-He's grilling the nectarines.
-Nectarines.

660
00:27:07,158 --> 00:27:09,494
-He's grilling them.
-He is.

661
00:27:09,561 --> 00:27:11,029
That's why he put it on high heat.

662
00:27:11,096 --> 00:27:12,831
He needs high heat to make grill marks.

663
00:27:12,897 --> 00:27:16,401
-I see. To make the grill marks.
-They look good.

664
00:27:16,468 --> 00:27:20,105
-It'll smell nicely burnt and sweet.
-Yes.

665
00:27:20,171 --> 00:27:22,540
He wants to make the grill marks.

666
00:27:23,375 --> 00:27:24,275
They look pretty.

667
00:27:24,342 --> 00:27:28,647
-The nectarines look pretty.
-That's why he grilled those.

668
00:27:28,713 --> 00:27:30,081
It's like grill marks on steak.

669
00:27:30,148 --> 00:27:31,416
Is he taking those to the fridge?

670
00:27:31,483 --> 00:27:34,152
-It goes into the freezer.
-Into the freezer?

671
00:27:34,219 --> 00:27:35,186
He's chilling those.

672
00:27:35,253 --> 00:27:36,554
A DISH GOES IN AS WELL

673
00:27:36,621 --> 00:27:37,922
After grilling them?

674
00:27:37,989 --> 00:27:39,557
Will it get cold enough?

675
00:27:39,624 --> 00:27:41,593
But he only charred it on the outside.

676
00:27:41,660 --> 00:27:43,728
You have nine minutes left.

677
00:27:43,795 --> 00:27:46,398
Poong is trying to cool the tomatoes.

678
00:27:46,464 --> 00:27:48,733
-Yes.
-He hasn't peeled those yet,

679
00:27:48,800 --> 00:27:51,770
so we can't call those marinaded.

680
00:27:52,671 --> 00:27:53,905
Hey, wait.

681
00:27:53,972 --> 00:27:55,507
ADDING MORE SWEETNESS

682
00:27:55,573 --> 00:27:57,208
-It's almost like <i>cheong</i>.
-It'll cause diabetes.

683
00:27:57,275 --> 00:27:59,778
-That's honey. Sugar and honey?
-Honey.

684
00:27:59,844 --> 00:28:02,180
Just looking at that
gave me clogged veins.

685
00:28:02,247 --> 00:28:04,082
TAKING HOT TOMATOES SOMEWHERE

686
00:28:04,149 --> 00:28:06,351
It's like tomato <i>cheong</i>.

687
00:28:06,418 --> 00:28:08,553
Yes, something like that.

688
00:28:09,954 --> 00:28:11,222
The timer went off.

689
00:28:12,691 --> 00:28:14,225
CHECKS THE OVEN

690
00:28:16,261 --> 00:28:18,229
MAKING NECTARINE DRESSING

691
00:28:18,296 --> 00:28:21,566
He grilled some nectarines
and put those in the freezer,

692
00:28:21,633 --> 00:28:23,902
and he's using another one with honey.

693
00:28:24,602 --> 00:28:26,071
Is he using a blender?

694
00:28:30,775 --> 00:28:32,677
ADDING GROUND PEPPER

695
00:28:33,778 --> 00:28:35,113
That's nectarine sauce.

696
00:28:35,180 --> 00:28:37,682
He added honey and balsamic vinegar
into the leftover nectarine

697
00:28:37,749 --> 00:28:40,819
-and made dressing, I think.
-Dressing?

698
00:28:41,386 --> 00:28:44,489
COOLING THE DRESSING TOO

699
00:28:44,556 --> 00:28:46,257
POONG USES EGGS

700
00:28:46,858 --> 00:28:49,427
HE BREAKS THE EGGS WILDLY TOO(?)

701
00:28:49,994 --> 00:28:53,031
EASILY PICKS SHELLS OUT

702
00:28:53,665 --> 00:28:54,999
He added chicken stock to eggs.

703
00:28:55,066 --> 00:28:56,101
The important thing must be

704
00:28:56,167 --> 00:28:59,437
that he'll fry beaten eggs
instead of making fried eggs.

705
00:28:59,504 --> 00:29:00,939
-He beat the eggs.
-He did?

706
00:29:01,573 --> 00:29:02,807
AT THAT TIME, THE OIL BEGINS TO SPLATTER

707
00:29:02,874 --> 00:29:04,008
The oil is too hot.

708
00:29:04,075 --> 00:29:06,277
Is it? Dang it. Wait.

709
00:29:06,344 --> 00:29:07,645
-This is bad.
-It's over 230 degrees.

710
00:29:08,213 --> 00:29:09,881
RUNNING ABOUT IN CONFUSION

711
00:29:09,948 --> 00:29:12,283
-The oil is too hot.
-It's too hot?

712
00:29:13,384 --> 00:29:16,454
-The oil?
-The oil is too hot, so he adds more oil.

713
00:29:17,622 --> 00:29:18,823
Yes, dang it.

714
00:29:18,890 --> 00:29:21,025
-Can't it be too high?
-No.

715
00:29:21,092 --> 00:29:22,594
Can you tell us what the reason is?

716
00:29:22,660 --> 00:29:24,229
It'll burn.

717
00:29:25,797 --> 00:29:27,432
-Yes.
-It'll burn.

718
00:29:27,499 --> 00:29:29,000
We know that.

719
00:29:29,067 --> 00:29:30,268
He's done with the chili oil.

720
00:29:31,202 --> 00:29:35,073
Kyung-soo doesn't like seeing drips
on the side of bowls.

721
00:29:35,140 --> 00:29:36,908
-No.
-He likes people who keep things clean.

722
00:29:36,975 --> 00:29:39,644
Poong's side looks too messy.

723
00:29:39,711 --> 00:29:41,412
THE NEAT ICE PRINCE

724
