00:48:56,600 --> 00:48:58,435
Japanese, confectionery,
baking, and brewing.

1212
00:48:58,502 --> 00:49:00,304
-I see.
-Other than those,

1213
00:49:00,370 --> 00:49:03,173
I'm even licensed
in coffee, wine, and tea,

1214
00:49:03,240 --> 00:49:04,541
everything you can think of.

1215
00:49:04,608 --> 00:49:06,109
He's so diligent.

1216
00:49:06,176 --> 00:49:09,746
It's probably only a few if you leave out
non-state-certified licenses.

1217
00:49:09,813 --> 00:49:11,748
-I have seven of those.
-The licenses aren't legit?

1218
00:49:11,815 --> 00:49:13,317
-Seven?
-Yes.

1219
00:49:13,383 --> 00:49:14,484
You lived a diligent life.

1220
00:49:15,852 --> 00:49:17,621
-Thanks.
-He lived a diligent life.

1221
00:49:17,688 --> 00:49:19,189
That was heartwarming.

1222
00:49:19,823 --> 00:49:21,191
What's with them?

1223
00:49:21,258 --> 00:49:23,894
Well, the order you'll fill is titled,

1224
00:49:23,961 --> 00:49:25,562
D.O.ryangjin Fish Market.

1225
00:49:25,629 --> 00:49:28,398
I find Noryangjin very comfortable.

1226
00:49:28,465 --> 00:49:29,666
I've gone there often

1227
00:49:29,733 --> 00:49:32,202
since I was very young,
because I loved raw fish.

1228
00:49:32,269 --> 00:49:35,038
You haven't been
to Noryangjin often, right?

1229
00:49:35,105 --> 00:49:38,108
I haven't. Meanwhile,
I went around trying to get licensed.

1230
00:49:39,676 --> 00:49:42,379
He already lost this argument twice.

1231
00:49:42,446 --> 00:49:43,547
He can't win.

1232
00:49:44,481 --> 00:49:46,483
CHEF NAM-NO'S INGREDIENTS: CAULIFLOWER,
THYME, APPLE MINT, SCALLOP, HORNED TURBAN

1233
00:49:46,550 --> 00:49:48,552
VENUS CLAM, BISCUIT, LEMON, ALMOND,
BLACKTHROAT SEAPERCH, PARSLEY

1234
00:49:48,618 --> 00:49:50,020
The dish I prepared is called

1235
00:49:50,988 --> 00:49:52,589
Yoon Nam-Noryangjin.

1236
00:49:52,656 --> 00:49:54,524
-Yoon Nam-Noryangjin.
-Yoon Nam-Noryangjin.

1237
00:49:54,591 --> 00:49:55,892
Your name was useful.

1238
00:49:55,959 --> 00:49:59,696
-I'm going to make a French dish today.
-Really?

1239
00:49:59,763 --> 00:50:03,367
Escargot, a snail dish,
must be the most famous French dish.

1240
00:50:03,433 --> 00:50:05,302
Wait, escargot?

1241
00:50:05,369 --> 00:50:08,705
I'll use horned turbans,
which are similar to snails,

1242
00:50:08,772 --> 00:50:11,108
to make a similar dish for him.

1243
00:50:11,174 --> 00:50:13,944
It'd be a shame
if I served just the shellfish,

1244
00:50:14,011 --> 00:50:16,313
so I'll use blackthroat seaperch,
Venus clams, and scallops

1245
00:50:16,380 --> 00:50:19,649
-to make a delicious seafood dish.
-Will he have enough time?

1246
00:50:20,584 --> 00:50:22,052
CHEF SUNG-JUN'S INGREDIENTS: ALMOND,
PARMIGIANO, THREELINE GRUNT, TOMATO PASTE

1247
00:50:22,119 --> 00:50:23,553
CAULIFLOWER, VENUS CLAM, FRESH CREAM,
SCALLOP, WHISKEY, THYME, SQUID, AND MORE

1248
00:50:23,620 --> 00:50:25,255
The dish I'm making is

1249
00:50:25,889 --> 00:50:27,357
Noryangjin Matfia.

1250
00:50:27,424 --> 00:50:28,992
-Noryangjin Matfia?
-Noryangjin Matfia?

1251
00:50:29,059 --> 00:50:31,461
You're using Matfia for everything.

1252
00:50:31,528 --> 00:50:33,363
There's a cooking method
called cartoccio in Italy,

1253
00:50:33,430 --> 00:50:35,065
also known as papillote in French.

1254
00:50:35,132 --> 00:50:39,102
It's a way to roast seafood
by covering everything in parchment paper.

1255
00:50:39,169 --> 00:50:41,772
-Threeline grunt is also in season,
-Threeline grunt.

1256
00:50:41,838 --> 00:50:43,540
so I plan to use that.

1257
00:50:43,607 --> 00:50:46,610
I'll also use
Venus clams, squid, scallops,

1258
00:50:46,676 --> 00:50:49,046
and stalked sea squirt to add a touch.

1259
00:50:49,112 --> 00:50:51,014
-Stalked sea squirts?
-Stalked sea squirts?

1260
00:50:51,081 --> 00:50:52,816
-It could be too much.
-It has a strong smell.

1261
00:50:52,883 --> 00:50:54,785
I like it a lot.

1262
00:50:54,851 --> 00:50:56,887
I love the ocean smell,

1263
00:50:56,953 --> 00:50:58,889
and I eat everything very well.

1264
00:50:58,955 --> 00:51:02,492
-That sounds good.
-I also want to present the Italian flag,

1265
00:51:02,559 --> 00:51:04,161
green, red, and white,

1266
00:51:04,227 --> 00:51:06,296
by preparing three difference sauces.

1267
00:51:06,363 --> 00:51:08,465
This is a match between countries.

1268
00:51:08,532 --> 00:51:11,635
This is Italy versus France.

1269
00:51:11,701 --> 00:51:14,571
I think they'd look similar if they had

1270
00:51:14,638 --> 00:51:16,473
a similar hairstyle.

1271
00:51:16,540 --> 00:51:18,275
Now that we're here,

1272
00:51:18,341 --> 00:51:20,343
let's make a bet on their hairstyle.

1273
00:51:20,410 --> 00:51:21,745
-The hairstyle.
-The hair.

1274
00:51:21,812 --> 00:51:25,715
-The loser can copy the winner like twins.
-Copy the winner.

1275
00:51:25,782 --> 00:51:26,850
That sounds fun.

1276
00:51:26,917 --> 00:51:28,485
I'm in.

1277
00:51:28,552 --> 00:51:30,087
You are?

1278
00:51:30,153 --> 00:51:31,455
-You'll do this hair?
-Yes.

1279
00:51:32,255 --> 00:51:33,990
You'll bleach your hair if you lose.

1280
00:51:34,057 --> 00:51:36,126
Bleaching my hair? Okay.

1281
00:51:36,193 --> 00:51:38,261
What if I lose?

1282
00:51:38,328 --> 00:51:40,263
Whoa, this is a tough fight.

1283
00:51:40,330 --> 00:51:42,532
And now, let us begin the round

1284
00:51:42,599 --> 00:51:45,335
D.O.ryangjin Fish Market.

1285
00:51:45,902 --> 00:51:48,105
THEIR HAIRSTYLES ARE AT STAKE!

1286
00:51:48,171 --> 00:51:49,473
They bet their hairstyle.

1287
00:51:49,539 --> 00:51:51,408
Noryangjin is his turf.

1288
00:51:51,475 --> 00:51:55,679
The world-class military cook is
here to take the star for free.

1289
00:51:55,745 --> 00:51:57,848
It's Chef Yoon Nam-no.

1290
00:51:57,914 --> 00:52:01,218
The military cook who likes to travel
already took over Naples,

1291
00:52:01,284 --> 00:52:04,621
Sichuan, and Osaka,
so it's now his turn to take Noryangjin.

1292
00:52:04,688 --> 00:52:07,457
It's Chef Kwon Sung-jun.

1293
00:52:07,524 --> 00:52:10,794
Which one of them will
end up with a new hairstyle?

1294
00:52:11,962 --> 00:52:15,031
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1295
00:52:17,734 --> 00:52:19,035
Begin!

1296
00:52:19,102 --> 00:52:21,638
WHO'LL BECOME THE BEST MILITARY COOK?

1297
00:52:21,705 --> 00:52:23,540
-Let me use the microwave.
-It's a new kind of fight.

1298
00:52:23,607 --> 00:52:26,209
No, our hair is at stake.
You can't use mine.

1299
00:52:26,276 --> 00:52:27,310
HOW CUTE

1300
00:52:27,377 --> 00:52:29,746
-Let me use the microwave.
-The microwave.

1301
00:52:29,813 --> 00:52:32,749
Isn't it harder to cook
when you have too many ingredients?

1302
00:52:32,816 --> 00:52:34,518
-Of course.
-There are too many.

1303
00:52:34,584 --> 00:52:37,554
When there are too many key ingredients,

1304
00:52:37,621 --> 00:52:39,923
it can throw off the balance.

1305
00:52:39,990 --> 00:52:40,924
READY TO SHOOT FIRE!

1306
00:52:42,359 --> 00:52:44,594
He's grilling clams.

1307
00:52:44,661 --> 00:52:46,630
He's grilling Venus clams.

1308
00:52:47,531 --> 00:52:48,999
-Venus clams.
-Look.

1309
00:52:49,065 --> 00:52:50,901
-They'll open up.
-No.

1310
00:52:50,967 --> 00:52:53,937
Venus clams are tough to open
compared to other clams.

1311
00:52:54,004 --> 00:52:56,373
At times, it still won't open
even after it's cooked.

1312
00:52:56,439 --> 00:52:57,541
Really?

1313
00:52:57,607 --> 00:52:58,441
BUT THEY'RE OPENING UP

1314
00:52:58,508 --> 00:52:59,342
It just opened up.

1315
00:52:59,409 --> 00:53:01,778
It opens up easily over high heat.

1316
00:53:01,845 --> 00:53:04,915
I've seen Venus clams
that won't when I had the soup.

1317
00:53:04,981 --> 00:53:05,849
It's tough to open.

1318
00:53:05,916 --> 00:53:07,584
So that's how it's done.

1319
00:53:08,518 --> 00:53:10,086
FIGHTING VENUS CLAMS
WITH MORE VENUS CLAMS

1320
00:53:10,153 --> 00:53:11,922
He's using the same method.

1321
00:53:11,988 --> 00:53:13,990
But his clams go into a pan.

1322
00:53:14,624 --> 00:53:17,694
I wonder how he'll use
the stalked sea squirts.

1323
00:53:18,361 --> 00:53:20,363
He grabs the threeline grunt first.

1324
00:53:20,964 --> 00:53:23,333
-There were two of those.
-Yes.

1325
00:53:23,400 --> 00:53:26,303
Is there a reason
why you like threeline grunt?

1326
00:53:26,369 --> 00:53:28,438
It's just really good. It's a good fish.

1327
00:53:28,505 --> 00:53:29,606
Is it?

1328
00:53:29,673 --> 00:53:32,609
It has a great texture too.

1329
00:53:32,676 --> 00:53:34,511
It has a lot of fat,

1330
00:53:34,578 --> 00:53:36,479
so when you grill it,

1331
00:53:36,546 --> 00:53:38,815
it'll begin to bubble
up because of the fat.

1332
00:53:38,882 --> 00:53:40,317
-It's that fatty?
-Is it really?

1333
00:53:40,383 --> 00:53:42,586
-He must enjoy that flavor.
-Yes.

1334
00:53:42,652 --> 00:53:46,790
3. GRILL THREELINE GRUNT FILLET
IN OLIVE OIL, SALT, AND PEPPER

1335
00:53:46,856 --> 00:53:48,658
There's the blackthroat seaperch.

1336
00:53:48,725 --> 00:53:49,993
You have to move quickly to clean fish.

1337
00:53:50,060 --> 00:53:53,263
Blackthroat seaperch has very tender meat.

1338
00:53:53,330 --> 00:53:56,566
-It's like dried yellow corvina.
-It's like yellow corvina.

1339
00:53:56,633 --> 00:53:59,469
It has a nice texture
and is considered a high-end fish.

1340
00:53:59,536 --> 00:54:02,939
-Yes.
-And blackthroat seaperch is even fattier.

1341
00:54:03,506 --> 00:54:07,244
3. SEASON BLACKTHROAT SEAPERCH FILLET
WITH SALT

1342
00:54:07,811 --> 00:54:09,512
WHISKEY?

1343
00:54:09,579 --> 00:54:10,914
Chef Sung-jun.

1344
00:54:10,981 --> 00:54:12,549
He's feeding it alcohol to open them up.

1345
00:54:13,116 --> 00:54:14,351
That's a lot of work.

1346
00:54:15,318 --> 00:54:17,687
-Flambé.
-I'm adding the whiskey smell by flambé.

1347
00:54:17,754 --> 00:54:20,123
He's getting the clams drunk.

1348
00:54:20,190 --> 00:54:21,992
Let me borrow your tongs.

1349
00:54:22,058 --> 00:54:23,560
Grilled clams.

1350
00:54:25,996 --> 00:54:27,464
IT WAS EFFECTIVE!

1351
00:54:27,530 --> 00:54:30,267
HE GETS THREE OPENED VENUS CLAMS

1352
00:54:30,333 --> 00:54:31,234
Scallops.

1353
00:54:31,301 --> 00:54:32,569
Scallops look good.

1354
00:54:33,136 --> 00:54:35,005
MAKING LARGE PIECES

1355
00:54:35,505 --> 00:54:38,241
4. GRILL SCALLOPS IN A PAN

1356
00:54:38,308 --> 00:54:39,709
ONE MORE DASH OF WHISKEY!

1357
00:54:39,776 --> 00:54:42,212
5. POUR WHISKEY TO FLAMBÉ
VENUS CLAMS AND STALKED SEA SQUIRTS

1358
00:54:42,279 --> 00:54:43,513
He keeps setting them on fire.

1359
00:54:44,180 --> 00:54:46,616
They have different ways
of setting those on fire.

1360
00:54:47,617 --> 00:54:50,787
THE THREELINE GRUNT TURNS GOLDEN BROWN

1361
00:54:50,854 --> 00:54:52,422
You should flip the clams.

1362
00:54:53,523 --> 00:54:55,925
He's almost burning them.

1363
00:54:55,992 --> 00:54:57,761
-The shell!
-Did it break?

1364
00:54:57,827 --> 00:55:00,830
-The shell.
-The shell completely broke apart.

1365
00:55:00,897 --> 00:55:02,866
He just cremated the Venus clam.

1366
00:55:04,734 --> 00:55:07,737
He cremated the clams.

1367
00:55:07,804 --> 00:55:08,805
Was it a good death?

1368
00:55:10,040 --> 00:55:11,241
The clams.

1369
00:55:12,342 --> 00:55:13,777
He's using scallops too.

1370
00:55:13,843 --> 00:55:16,246
Nam-no uses scallops too.

1371
00:55:16,313 --> 00:55:18,882
-They're already…
-They both use scallops.

1372
00:55:18,948 --> 00:55:21,351
The ingredients
from Noryangjin are similar.

1373
00:55:23,386 --> 00:55:24,854
He keeps setting that on fire.

1374
00:55:24,921 --> 00:55:26,189
Whiskey.

1375
00:55:26,256 --> 00:55:28,658
-He'll do that until they open.
-They haven't opened.

1376
00:55:28,725 --> 00:55:30,460
Hey, open up.

1377
00:55:30,527 --> 00:55:33,430
-They won't open.
-I told you.

1378
00:55:33,496 --> 00:55:35,332
-Open up.
-Add just a little water.

1379
00:55:35,398 --> 00:55:36,733
I'll add some water.

1380
00:55:36,800 --> 00:55:38,668
The Venus clams won't open up.

1381
00:55:38,735 --> 00:55:40,236
Cover it with a lid.

1382
00:55:40,303 --> 00:55:42,539
-He only keeps adding more liquor.
-Yes.

1383
00:55:42,605 --> 00:55:45,875
Nam-no has a better way
of opening the clams.

1384
00:55:45,942 --> 00:55:48,478
Right? Chef Nam-no either opens them up

1385
00:55:48,545 --> 00:55:50,847
or just plain cremates them.

1386
00:55:50,914 --> 00:55:53,249
Nam-no's clams opened up ages ago.

1387
00:55:53,316 --> 00:55:54,250
POURS WATER AND CLOSES IT

1388
00:55:56,052 --> 00:55:57,754
-He's grinding parsley.
-Parsley.

1389
00:55:58,388 --> 00:55:59,656
Italian parsley.

1390
00:56:00,223 --> 00:56:02,359
ALMOND, BISCUITS

1391
00:56:02,926 --> 00:56:06,396
4. GRIND PARSLEY, ALMONDS,
AND BISCUITS IN A BLENDER

1392
00:56:06,930 --> 00:56:09,232
He's mixing parsley and butter.

1393
00:56:09,299 --> 00:56:11,801
-Parsley and butter.
-And almonds and biscuits.

1394
00:56:11,868 --> 00:56:14,237
-Biscuits? The snack?
-Yes, the snack.

1395
00:56:14,304 --> 00:56:17,140
Escargot dishes are made
by topping the snails

1396
00:56:17,207 --> 00:56:19,943
with a mix of butter and parsley,
so it must be that.

1397
00:56:20,009 --> 00:56:21,811
It looks like grass.

1398
00:56:21,878 --> 00:56:23,246
Why did you use biscuits?

1399
00:56:23,913 --> 00:56:25,248
It's usually made with breadcrumbs, so…

1400
00:56:25,315 --> 00:56:27,784
-Yes, he's right.
-Instead of breadcrumbs.

1401
00:56:27,851 --> 00:56:29,919
He's using horned turbans
instead of snails, right?

1402
00:56:29,986 --> 00:56:31,521
I didn't see any breadcrumbs.

1403
00:56:32,756 --> 00:56:34,524
ADDING PARSLEY BUTTER INTO A POT

1404
00:56:35,091 --> 00:56:36,659
GARLIC

1405
00:56:36,726 --> 00:56:38,595
ONION

1406
00:56:39,462 --> 00:56:44,401
5. BOIL PARSLEY BUTTER, GARLIC, AND ONION

1407
00:56:45,402 --> 00:56:47,103
SUNG-JUN GET LEMON READY

1408
00:56:47,604 --> 00:56:49,339
BASIL, THYME

1409
00:56:49,406 --> 00:56:51,508
AND THREELINE GRUNT, SCALLOPS!

1410
00:56:51,574 --> 00:56:54,344
-Scallops, and…
-Are you already done?

1411
00:56:54,411 --> 00:56:56,179
-Is that it?
-He'll cover it with paper.

1412
00:56:56,246 --> 00:56:58,915
Cartoccio is a way of cooking
by covering the fish

1413
00:56:58,982 --> 00:57:00,817
with some parchment paper.

1414
00:57:00,884 --> 00:57:03,987
It's mostly cooked with moisture
in the oven.

1415
00:57:04,053 --> 00:57:05,822
You'll rip the paper
right before you eat it.

1416
00:57:05,889 --> 00:57:07,690
He's wrapping it with parchment paper.

1417
00:57:07,757 --> 00:57:09,826
6. ROAST THREELINE GRUNT, SCALLOP,
LEMON, AND HERBS IN PARCHMENT PAPER

1418
00:57:10,627 --> 00:57:12,295
Are you burning these?

1419
00:57:12,362 --> 00:57:13,696
Yes, I am.

1420
00:57:14,297 --> 00:57:17,867
6. COAT SLICED SCALLOPS

1421
00:57:17,934 --> 00:57:21,471
WITH OLIVE OIL AND BROIL

1422
00:57:23,072 --> 00:57:24,240
Are you open yet?

1423
00:57:24,307 --> 00:57:26,910
-They aren't open.
-They aren't!

1424
00:57:26,976 --> 00:57:29,512
The Venus clams won't open up.

1425
00:57:29,579 --> 00:57:30,980
They're taciturn.

1426
00:57:31,047 --> 00:57:34,784
I think I'm starting to see
your bleached hair.

1427
00:57:34,851 --> 00:57:37,020
I think your hair is bleached a little.

1428
00:57:37,086 --> 00:57:38,855
-Already?
-Your hair already looks bleached.

1429
00:57:38,922 --> 00:57:39,756
Bleached hair.

1430
00:57:39,823 --> 00:57:42,225
Nam-no is on smooth sail so far.

1431
00:57:44,060 --> 00:57:47,530
BROILED THE SCALLOPS SMOOTHLY

1432
00:57:49,799 --> 00:57:52,635
-Sung-jun's hair is changing colors.
-No!

1433
00:57:52,702 --> 00:57:53,870
BASIL, ALMONDS

1434
00:57:53,937 --> 00:57:55,905
Sung-jun's hair is in a different color.

1435
00:57:55,972 --> 00:57:58,441
I think he's blending something with oil.

1436
00:57:58,508 --> 00:58:00,643
It looks like classic pesto.

1437
00:58:00,710 --> 00:58:02,412
-Yes.
-Garlic.

1438
00:58:02,479 --> 00:58:06,249
He mentioned three colors of
the Italian flag, red, green, and white.

1439
00:58:06,850 --> 00:58:08,151
That must be the green sauce.

1440
00:58:08,218 --> 00:58:09,552
GREEN SAUCE: BASIL PESTO

1441
00:58:10,086 --> 00:58:11,454
Yes.

1442
00:58:11,521 --> 00:58:13,656
It's turning green.

1443
00:58:13,723 --> 00:58:14,724
You have eight minutes.

1444
00:58:14,791 --> 00:58:16,759
7. MAKE BASIL PESTO WITH BASIL, OLIVE OIL,
ALMOND, GARLIC, AND PARMIGIANO

1445
00:58:16,826 --> 00:58:18,695
-Whoa!
-It's overflowing!

1446
00:58:18,761 --> 00:58:20,196
-The Venus clams.
-They're open.

1447
00:58:20,263 --> 00:58:21,397
Okay.

1448
00:58:22,065 --> 00:58:23,833
-Have they opened?
-They have.

1449
00:58:23,900 --> 00:58:25,401
The Venus clams have opened up

1450
00:58:25,468 --> 00:58:28,271
His hair is turning back to black.

1451
00:58:28,338 --> 00:58:31,174
Chef Sung-jun, are you using that broth?

1452
00:58:31,241 --> 00:58:33,877
-That broth already looks delicious.
-He seasons the broth.

1453
00:58:33,943 --> 00:58:35,311
That's tomato paste.

1454
00:58:35,378 --> 00:58:37,447
-Is that the red sauce?
-Tomato paste.

1455
00:58:37,514 --> 00:58:39,482
Their ingredients are almost the same,

1456
00:58:39,549 --> 00:58:43,453
but one of them cooks Italian food,
while the other cooks French.

1457
00:58:43,520 --> 00:58:45,154
Why are you so nearby? Move further.

1458
00:58:45,221 --> 00:58:47,357
-This is my turf.
-Stop bickering.

1459
00:58:47,423 --> 00:58:49,225
They seem to be great friends.

1460
00:58:50,026 --> 00:58:52,695
-Horned turbans.
-Are those cooked?

1461
00:58:53,263 --> 00:58:55,665
7. WASH HORNED TURBANS IN COLD WATER
AND COOL THEM DOWN

1462
00:58:55,732 --> 00:58:57,634
Gosh, we have five minutes left.

1463
00:58:58,768 --> 00:59:00,603
-No.
-Six minutes left.

1464
00:59:04,173 --> 00:59:05,008
OH! IT'S HOT

1465
00:59:05,575 --> 00:59:07,744
He's cooking blackthroat seaperch.

1466
00:59:07,810 --> 00:59:09,245
What are those? Right.

1467
00:59:09,312 --> 00:59:10,980
-Cauliflower.
-Cauliflower.

1468
00:59:11,047 --> 00:59:12,415
-It's hot.
-That must be the white sauce.

1469
00:59:12,482 --> 00:59:13,750
-It's hot!
-Is it for color?

1470
00:59:13,816 --> 00:59:15,285
-That's the white sauce,
-It's hot!

1471
00:59:15,351 --> 00:59:18,488
The Italian flag sauce. It's still hot!

1472
00:59:18,555 --> 00:59:20,623
-So chefs find those hot too?
-Of course.

1473
00:59:21,724 --> 00:59:23,626
I thought it was just me.

1474
00:59:23,693 --> 00:59:25,228
He's using fresh cream too.

1475
00:59:25,295 --> 00:59:28,631
Yes, Sung-jun continuously
grinds something.

1476
00:59:28,698 --> 00:59:32,502
He added butter, garlic, and cheese
into cauliflower.

1477
00:59:32,569 --> 00:59:34,971
-That's wireless?
-Yes, it's wireless.

1478
00:59:35,038 --> 00:59:37,740
-Is that the white of the flag?
-I think so.

1479
00:59:37,807 --> 00:59:39,876
The horned turbans.

1480
00:59:39,943 --> 00:59:41,578
He added fresh cream there?

1481
00:59:41,644 --> 00:59:42,478
Jeez.

1482
00:59:42,545 --> 00:59:44,247
-It's hot.
-You find those hot too?

1483
00:59:44,314 --> 00:59:45,715
That was so human.

1484
00:59:45,782 --> 00:59:46,916
CUTTING OFF THE INNARDS

1485
00:59:46,983 --> 00:59:48,685
You just put up with it?

1486
00:59:48,751 --> 00:59:50,286
ADDING TO PARSLEY BUTTER!

1487
00:59:50,353 --> 00:59:51,621
You're cooking everything together?

1488
00:59:51,688 --> 00:59:53,389
It looks so good.

1489
00:59:53,456 --> 00:59:55,491
8. ADD HORNED TURBANS, SCALLOPS,
AND VENUS CLAMS INTO THE PARSLEY BUTTER

1490
00:59:55,558 --> 00:59:56,526
Look at that.

1491
00:59:56,593 --> 00:59:59,395
The blackthroat seaperch is
grilled deliciously in golden brown.

1492
00:59:59,462 --> 01:00:01,631
Sung-ju, tell us what's
going on out there.

1493
01:00:01,698 --> 01:00:03,132
-Yes.
-You have five minutes!

1494
01:00:03,199 --> 01:00:05,435
Five minutes. Let me rush out.

1495
01:00:05,501 --> 01:00:07,804
It's a fight between two military cooks.

1496
01:00:07,870 --> 01:00:08,771
Squid?

1497
01:00:08,838 --> 01:00:10,807
How is he going to use that squid?

1498
01:00:10,873 --> 01:00:12,609
Who'll be chosen in the end?

1499
01:00:12,675 --> 01:00:16,446
I'm the eldest former military cook here,

1500
01:00:16,512 --> 01:00:18,548
reporting for you from the scene.

1501
01:00:18,615 --> 01:00:22,452
-I don't know if they're doing well.
-Forty seconds.

1502
01:00:22,518 --> 01:00:26,990
Consider our guest today
as important as the division commander.

1503
01:00:27,056 --> 01:00:29,425
Make sure you cook well.

1504
01:00:29,492 --> 01:00:32,528
Private Yoon, why are you
keeping the heat on as you work?

1505
01:00:32,595 --> 01:00:35,498
Hey! This is all costing taxpayers' money.

1506
01:00:35,565 --> 01:00:36,733
-Private Yoon!
-I'm sorry, sir!

1507
01:00:36,799 --> 01:00:37,700
Turn the heat off.

1508
01:00:37,767 --> 01:00:40,937
What if the commander sees this?

1509
01:00:41,004 --> 01:00:43,206
He'll get mad at me.

1510
01:00:43,272 --> 01:00:44,974
That's such an ancient way of acting.

1511
01:00:46,142 --> 01:00:47,644
"He'll get mad at me."

1512
01:00:48,945 --> 01:00:50,480
Right, we have an actor here.

1513
01:00:50,546 --> 01:00:52,982
-How do you do it now?
-Hide all your feelings.

1514
01:00:53,616 --> 01:00:56,252
-You can't do that.
-Then how is it done?

1515
01:00:56,319 --> 01:00:58,021
Mutter to yourself.

1516
01:00:58,087 --> 01:01:00,223
He'll get mad at me.

1517
01:01:00,289 --> 01:01:01,624
Oh, rather like that?

1518
01:01:01,691 --> 01:01:03,192
One more time. How is it done?

1519
01:01:03,259 --> 01:01:04,527
Private Yoon.

1520
01:01:04,594 --> 01:01:07,130
When the commander sees this,
he'll get mad at me.

1521
01:01:07,697 --> 01:01:10,299
Stop! Do it over!

1522
01:01:10,366 --> 01:01:11,501
Who cast that guy?

1523
01:01:11,567 --> 01:01:13,603
His line suddenly popped out.

1524
01:01:13,670 --> 01:01:16,539
-Clean up as you go.
-I'm doing that now, sir.

1525
01:01:16,606 --> 01:01:19,809
How many stoves are you using?
Just use one.

1526
01:01:19,876 --> 01:01:21,044
-Corporal Kwon.
-Yes, sir?

1527
01:01:21,110 --> 01:01:22,612
-Corporal Kwon.
-Yes, sir?

1528
01:01:22,679 --> 01:01:23,746
He's answering very smoothly.

1529
01:01:23,813 --> 01:01:25,148
-Yes, sir.
-State your rank and name

1530
01:01:25,214 --> 01:01:26,516
when you're addressed!

1531
01:01:27,183 --> 01:01:28,117
Sergeant Kwon Sung-jun, sir.

1532
01:01:28,184 --> 01:01:30,453
-You have to state your rank and name.
-Sergeant Kwon Sung-jun, sir.

1533
01:01:30,520 --> 01:01:32,155
It's yet another awful skit.

1534
01:01:33,289 --> 01:01:35,992
They're busy cooking and playing along.

1535
01:01:36,059 --> 01:01:39,729
That's what I'm talking about.
Make sure you do a good job.

1536
01:01:39,796 --> 01:01:40,863
-Sung-jun.
-Yes?

1537
01:01:40,930 --> 01:01:42,465
Can you try that soup?

1538
01:01:42,532 --> 01:01:46,235
-The Venus clams.
-Byung-eun said it'd taste good.

1539
01:01:46,302 --> 01:01:49,305
Is it delicious enough
to let him go on leave?

1540
01:01:49,372 --> 01:01:50,807
It must be good.

1541
01:01:50,873 --> 01:01:53,209
-It's impossible for that to be bad.
-It'll be good.

1542
01:01:53,276 --> 01:01:54,711
Will he get to go on leave?

1543
01:01:56,746 --> 01:01:58,214
-My gosh.
-What is it?

1544
01:01:58,281 --> 01:01:59,582
It must be all right.

1545
01:01:59,649 --> 01:02:01,484
It's not good enough
to let him take leave.

1546
01:02:01,551 --> 01:02:03,720
-How about just an outing?
-Try a little harder.

1547
01:02:03,786 --> 01:02:05,588
It's not worth giving leave for.

1548
01:02:05,655 --> 01:02:07,523
-It's not so bad.
-Just an outing?

1549
01:02:07,590 --> 01:02:09,358
-A night outside?
-Spend a night outside?

1550
01:02:09,425 --> 01:02:10,960
You have three minutes left.

1551
01:02:11,661 --> 01:02:13,563
SEAFOOD GOES ON TOP
OF THE GREEN BASIL PESTO SAUCE

1552
01:02:14,130 --> 01:02:16,499
12. TOP THE BASIL PESTO
WITH COOKED SQUID AND STALKED SEA SQUIRTS

1553
01:02:16,566 --> 01:02:17,400
STALKED SEA SQUIRT

1554
01:02:19,635 --> 01:02:21,637
STRAIN THE LEFTOVER WHISKEY BRAISE

1555
01:02:21,704 --> 01:02:26,209
RED SAUCE: TOMATO WHISKEY BRAISE SOUP

1556
01:02:26,275 --> 01:02:28,878
Whoa, what is this?

1557
01:02:28,945 --> 01:02:30,279
Parsley butter. You can try it.

1558
01:02:30,346 --> 01:02:31,447
You can have the seafood too.

1559
01:02:31,514 --> 01:02:34,917
-Parsley butter?
-I'm trying just the sauce.

1560
01:02:34,984 --> 01:02:37,386
Gosh, Private Yoon.

1561
01:02:37,453 --> 01:02:39,689
Is he worthy of the title world-class?

1562
01:02:41,491 --> 01:02:43,292
Is he worthy of the title world-class?

1563
01:02:44,494 --> 01:02:45,962
I'm in France!

1564
01:02:46,028 --> 01:02:48,631
Where did you learn to do this?

1565
01:02:48,698 --> 01:02:49,866
I DID IT!

1566
01:02:49,932 --> 01:02:50,767
Where did you learn this?

1567
01:02:50,833 --> 01:02:52,034
You have two minutes left.

1568
01:02:52,101 --> 01:02:54,537
You brought such a smart kid here.

1569
01:02:54,604 --> 01:02:57,507
I'm glad we have Private Yoon here.

1570
01:02:57,573 --> 01:03:00,610
10. CHOP CAULIFLOWER
AND APPLE MINT INTO TINY PIECES

1571
01:03:00,676 --> 01:03:03,379
This is a promotional video for our troop.

1572
01:03:03,446 --> 01:03:05,014
You must do well for PR.

1573
01:03:05,081 --> 01:03:08,217
Kyung-soo is from our military base!

1574
01:03:08,284 --> 01:03:10,820
You have a minute and 13 seconds.

1575
01:03:11,554 --> 01:03:16,993
11. MIX OLIVE OIL, SALT, AND PEPPER
TO MAKE CAULIFLOWER SALAD

1576
01:03:17,059 --> 01:03:20,196
Nam-no begins to serve his food.

1577
01:03:20,263 --> 01:03:21,864
What are you serving?

1578
01:03:21,931 --> 01:03:25,768
-Cauliflower salad. He can eat like rice.
-Like rice?

1579
01:03:25,835 --> 01:03:27,303
I can't hear you.

1580
01:03:27,370 --> 01:03:28,671
-Raise your voice!
-I'm sorry, sir!

1581
01:03:28,738 --> 01:03:30,640
Cauliflower steak… No, salad.

1582
01:03:30,706 --> 01:03:32,208
Tell me your name and rank!

1583
01:03:32,275 --> 01:03:34,143
THE HELLISH SKIT WON'T END

1584
01:03:34,210 --> 01:03:35,611
That's the white sauce.

1585
01:03:35,678 --> 01:03:37,180
What's that? Garlic?

1586
01:03:37,246 --> 01:03:39,582
-Cauliflower.
-He begins to serve his food too.

1587
01:03:39,649 --> 01:03:42,218
Sung-jun is representing the Italian flag.

1588
01:03:42,285 --> 01:03:44,220
-I see green and white.
-They're so good.

1589
01:03:44,287 --> 01:03:47,223
-You'll need red, now. Red.
-Yes, sir!

1590
01:03:47,290 --> 01:03:49,091
You have 50 seconds left.

1591
01:03:49,158 --> 01:03:51,160
Fifty seconds. Don't rush it.

1592
01:03:51,227 --> 01:03:53,296
-Is he done?
-Please hurry.

1593
01:03:53,362 --> 01:03:56,199
-It's for Kyung-soo.
-He's done with it now.

1594
01:03:56,265 --> 01:03:59,335
-Sergeant Doh will get discharged soon!
-Hurry up!

1595
01:03:59,402 --> 01:04:02,305
You have to cook well
for your predecessor.

1596
01:04:02,371 --> 01:04:05,007
You have 35 seconds left.

1597
01:04:05,074 --> 01:04:07,009
It's a mix of everything.

1598
01:04:07,076 --> 01:04:09,679
The red sauce, Sergeant Kwon.

1599
01:04:09,745 --> 01:04:12,014
-Where's the red sauce?
-It's coming, sir!

1600
01:04:12,081 --> 01:04:15,551
Is it? You only have 25 seconds.

1601
01:04:15,618 --> 01:04:18,087
Cooking is like a fight.
Cook individually!

1602
01:04:18,154 --> 01:04:19,555
Cook individually!

1603
01:04:19,622 --> 01:04:21,057
-Cook individually!
-Cook individually!

1604
01:04:21,123 --> 01:04:23,359
-Say it, Sergeant Kwon!
-Cook individually!

1605
01:04:23,426 --> 01:04:24,727
You have 14, 13, no, 12 seconds.

1606
01:04:24,794 --> 01:04:26,596
-Twelve seconds.
-Ten seconds!

1607
01:04:26,662 --> 01:04:28,865
-Ten. Nine. Eight.
-Nine Eight.

1608
01:04:28,931 --> 01:04:31,200
-Ten. Nine. Eight.
-Nine. Eight.

1609
01:04:31,267 --> 01:04:33,069
-Seven. Six.
-Seven. Six.

1610
01:04:33,135 --> 01:04:35,037
-Five. Four.
-Five. Time's almost up.

1611
01:04:35,104 --> 01:04:37,073
-Seven. Six.
-Seven. Six.

1612
01:04:37,139 --> 01:04:38,975
-Five. Four.
-Five. Time's almost up.

1613
01:04:39,041 --> 01:04:41,177
-Three. Two.
-The firearm will go off soon.

1614
01:04:41,244 --> 01:04:42,845
Hurry up and ring the bell.

1615
01:04:42,912 --> 01:04:46,449
-It's over!
-Sung-jun is all done too.

1616
01:04:47,149 --> 01:04:50,353
-Both Kwon and Yoon are done.
-Fifteen minutes flew by.

1617
01:04:50,419 --> 01:04:53,956
Please put your dishes here.
You can't add anything else now.

1618
01:04:54,023 --> 01:04:56,192
Look at the ingredients.

1619
01:04:56,259 --> 01:04:57,093
It looks good.

1620
01:04:57,159 --> 01:04:58,995
It looks good, Kyung-soo.

1621
01:04:59,061 --> 01:05:01,097
Yes, it looks good.

1622
01:05:01,163 --> 01:05:04,033
And now, both dishes for Kyung-soo's order

1623
01:05:04,100 --> 01:05:07,103
D.O.ryangjin Fish Market is done.

1624
01:05:07,169 --> 01:05:09,872
Well, the hairstyle
for our military cooks are at stake.

1625
01:05:09,939 --> 01:05:12,241
-Yes.
-He should make a wise decision.

1626
01:05:12,808 --> 01:05:15,111
Come to think of it, it's up to me.

1627
01:05:15,177 --> 01:05:17,613
-It is. Their hairstyle is on you.
-He's right.

1628
01:05:17,680 --> 01:05:19,382
I love these moments.

1629
01:05:21,350 --> 01:05:22,785
I'm glad that you like it.

1630
01:05:22,852 --> 01:05:24,620
But you'll have to try it first.

1631
01:05:24,687 --> 01:05:26,289
Yoon Nam-no the world-class cook.

1632
01:05:26,355 --> 01:05:28,357
Please try Yoon Nam-Noryangjin first.

1633
01:05:29,125 --> 01:05:31,994
NORYANGJIN IS MY PLAYGROUND!

1634
01:05:33,529 --> 01:05:37,700
NORYANGJIN SEAFOOD COOKED
IN ORIGINAL FRENCH ESCARGOT STYLE

1635
01:05:38,868 --> 01:05:41,604
CHEF YOON NAM-NO'S YOON NAM-NORYANGJIN

1636
01:05:41,671 --> 01:05:44,473
-My gosh.
-The blackthroat seaperch was…

1637
01:05:44,540 --> 01:05:46,208
The blackthroat seaperch…

1638
01:05:46,275 --> 01:05:47,410
Doesn't it smell good?

1639
01:05:47,476 --> 01:05:49,312
-It does.
-It already smells good.

1640
01:05:49,879 --> 01:05:51,280
RIGHT THEN, MILITARY COOK YOON WALKS OVER

1641
01:05:51,347 --> 01:05:54,216
It can be salty if you eat too much sauce.

1642
01:05:54,283 --> 01:05:56,585
I would've stayed in the army
if they served this kind of food.

1643
01:05:57,987 --> 01:06:00,489
Are you crazy?
I'd rather make money and buy the food.

1644
01:06:01,757 --> 01:06:03,926
-Why would you stay there?
-That's awful.

1645
01:06:03,993 --> 01:06:06,429
DIVIDING THE AMOUNT OF SAUCE

1646
01:06:06,495 --> 01:06:09,165
-Please try it like that.
-Thank you.

1647
01:06:09,231 --> 01:06:10,700
You're right.

1648
01:06:10,766 --> 01:06:12,601
-Thank you.
-First, scallops.

1649
01:06:13,736 --> 01:06:15,304
What do you eat that with?

1650
01:06:15,371 --> 01:06:17,139
Both ingredients are absolutely delicious.

1651
01:06:17,206 --> 01:06:19,809
I've never had blackthroat seaperch
with scallops before.

1652
01:06:19,875 --> 01:06:21,711
The green onion smell is great.

1653
01:06:21,777 --> 01:06:23,980
The sauce is like escargot.

1654
01:06:25,881 --> 01:06:27,817
Does it feel like France?

1655
01:06:27,883 --> 01:06:30,419
-What does that face mean?
-I see.

1656
01:06:30,486 --> 01:06:31,687
He must like it.

1657
01:06:32,321 --> 01:06:33,889
-It's insane.
-It is?

1658
01:06:34,690 --> 01:06:35,858
He looked at me and said it was insane.

1659
01:06:35,925 --> 01:06:39,261
But blackthroat seaperch and scallops
go very well in their textures.

1660
01:06:39,328 --> 01:06:42,298
Scallops are chewy,
while the fish melts in my mouth.

1661
01:06:42,365 --> 01:06:44,266
It's a lot of fun in my mouth.

1662
01:06:44,333 --> 01:06:46,702
And the sauce on top

1663
01:06:46,769 --> 01:06:49,872
may look a bit greasy
with all this oil, but not at all.

1664
01:06:49,939 --> 01:06:51,307
It's really good.

1665
01:06:51,374 --> 01:06:52,975
How am I supposed to express this?

1666
01:06:53,042 --> 01:06:54,510
-That's the right answer.
-It's really good.

1667
01:06:54,577 --> 01:06:56,946
The sauce is like escargot sauce?

1668
01:06:57,013 --> 01:06:59,682
-Let me try the Venus clam.
-Venus clam.

1669
01:07:00,416 --> 01:07:03,786
Those were broiled over fire.

1670
01:07:04,286 --> 01:07:06,355
It might have a bit of smoky flavor.

1671
01:07:06,422 --> 01:07:07,390
Grilled clams.

1672
01:07:08,124 --> 01:07:09,725
-Gosh.
-Yes?

1673
01:07:09,792 --> 01:07:10,993
The Venus clams are excellent.

1674
01:07:11,060 --> 01:07:12,428
HAPPY WITH THE VENUS CLAMS TOO

1675
01:07:12,495 --> 01:07:16,332
He didn't cook it for a long time,
so the clams are still soft.

1676
01:07:16,399 --> 01:07:17,833
FLINCHING

1677
01:07:17,900 --> 01:07:19,869
I get why you said
you were Yoon Nam-Noryangjin.

1678
01:07:20,870 --> 01:07:22,238
It was my playground.

1679
01:07:22,304 --> 01:07:24,173
-It was Nam-no's playground.
-Horned turbans.

1680
01:07:24,240 --> 01:07:25,441
Horned turbans.

1681
01:07:25,508 --> 01:07:27,276
-Gosh.
-It's not easy to cook those.

1682
01:07:27,343 --> 01:07:29,412
It's very easy to cut through these too.

1683
01:07:29,478 --> 01:07:31,380
-He cooked them very well.
-He did.

1684
01:07:32,848 --> 01:07:34,717
CAREFULLY TAKES A BITE

1685
01:07:36,919 --> 01:07:38,988
-The texture must be good.
-Yes, the texture.

1686
01:07:39,055 --> 01:07:41,257
-Horned turbans have their own texture.
-They do.

1687
01:07:41,323 --> 01:07:44,026
-It must be chewy.
-Anyway, it's really good.

1688
01:07:44,093 --> 01:07:46,162
It's not that one particular dish is good.

1689
01:07:46,228 --> 01:07:47,396
Everything is good, overall.

1690
01:07:47,463 --> 01:07:49,165
ALL SEAFOOD HERE IS DELICIOUS

1691
01:07:49,665 --> 01:07:51,734
Let me try the cauliflower.

1692
01:07:51,801 --> 01:07:54,703
-He told you to eat it like rice.
-He did.

1693
01:07:55,371 --> 01:07:57,606
It'll be good for you
if you ate that instead of rice.

1694
01:07:59,075 --> 01:08:00,943
It looks pretty greasy.

1695
01:08:02,244 --> 01:08:04,213
-Do you want some kimchi?
-Right?

1696
01:08:04,280 --> 01:08:05,448
Do you need kimchi?

1697
01:08:05,514 --> 01:08:07,583
It's not too greasy at all.

1698
01:08:07,650 --> 01:08:10,653
The Italian parsley adds
such a nice smell.

1699
01:08:10,719 --> 01:08:13,456
I can finish everything
even if I were served five bowls.

1700
01:08:13,522 --> 01:08:16,225
That's how easy it is to eat this.

1701
01:08:16,792 --> 01:08:19,428
-Can I really have this all?
-Yes, go ahead.

1702
01:08:19,495 --> 01:08:22,598
-You're the fridge owner.
-He likes the blackthroat seaperch.

1703
01:08:22,665 --> 01:08:25,701
-He tries a whole fillet.
-An entire fillet.

1704
01:08:25,768 --> 01:08:29,705
He liked all four ingredients,
but blackthroat seaperch was best.

1705
01:08:29,772 --> 01:08:31,907
-He has to eat this one too.
-Right?

1706
01:08:31,974 --> 01:08:34,844
-Sung-jun's hair will get bleached.
-Please try mine too.

1707
01:08:34,910 --> 01:08:36,879
You have to try this one too.

1708
01:08:36,946 --> 01:08:39,115
His hair is halfway bleached.

1709
01:08:39,181 --> 01:08:41,784
-He won't stop eating.
-Bleaching hair is…

1710
01:08:42,351 --> 01:08:44,854
Sung-jun is about to lose
his signature hair.

1711
01:08:44,920 --> 01:08:48,057
<i>Next, Chef Sung-jun's Noryangjin Matfia.</i>

1712
01:08:49,024 --> 01:08:52,061
THE THREE-COLORED SAUCE
AFTER THE ITALIAN FLAG

1713
01:08:53,362 --> 01:08:56,665
CHEF KWON SUNG-UN'S NORYANGJIN MATFIA

1714
01:08:57,366 --> 01:08:59,468
Let me cut this for you.

1715
01:08:59,535 --> 01:09:01,437
I wonder what's inside.

1716
01:09:01,504 --> 01:09:03,005
It takes too long.

1717
01:09:03,772 --> 01:09:06,976
-So Italians cook like this?
-Yes.

1718
01:09:07,042 --> 01:09:07,877
Try and smell it first.

1719
01:09:07,943 --> 01:09:10,045
It'll start smelling when he opens it.

1720
01:09:12,481 --> 01:09:13,983
-Whoa.
-Hey.

1721
01:09:14,049 --> 01:09:16,652
Thyme, basil, and other herbs

1722
01:09:16,719 --> 01:09:20,222
-on the bottom captures my nose first.
-They do?

1723
01:09:20,289 --> 01:09:22,258
He smells the dish first.

1724
01:09:22,324 --> 01:09:24,693
-Let me serve them on your dish.
-Thanks.

1725
01:09:24,760 --> 01:09:27,730
He's moving the ingredients.

1726
01:09:27,796 --> 01:09:30,432
Sung-jun must feel rushed.

1727
01:09:30,499 --> 01:09:33,569
He's in a rush
after Nam-no received a great response.

1728
01:09:34,136 --> 01:09:36,539
This isn't good.

1729
01:09:36,605 --> 01:09:40,176
-The military cooks' fight-off.
-He looks anxious.

1730
01:09:40,242 --> 01:09:41,410
KYUNG-SOO TRIES THE SAUCE FIRST

1731
01:09:41,477 --> 01:09:42,978
He tries the sauce first.

1732
01:09:43,045 --> 01:09:44,480
He focuses on the sauces.

1733
01:09:44,547 --> 01:09:47,149
He must like sauces.

1734
01:09:47,216 --> 01:09:48,984
The white sauce is like

1735
01:09:49,051 --> 01:09:50,319
aioli, right?

1736
01:09:50,886 --> 01:09:53,856
It's like a mix of garlic in mayonnaise.

1737
01:09:53,923 --> 01:09:57,092
The green sauce is similar to basil pesto,

1738
01:09:57,159 --> 01:09:59,662
and it's even nuttier with almonds.

1739
01:09:59,728 --> 01:10:01,030
Basil.

1740
01:10:01,096 --> 01:10:04,433
The red sauce was made with tomato paste,
so it's just tomato sauce.

1741
01:10:04,500 --> 01:10:06,268
I see. So it wasn't so special?

1742
01:10:06,335 --> 01:10:07,770
No, it's good.

1743
01:10:07,836 --> 01:10:10,005
<i>-It was made with clam broth.</i>
<i>-Yes.</i>

1744
01:10:10,072 --> 01:10:12,508
-Stalked sea squirts and clams.
-It's really good.

1745
01:10:12,575 --> 01:10:14,176
-That one.
-The actual dish.

1746
01:10:14,243 --> 01:10:16,879
-Let me try the threeline grunt.
-The threeline grunt.

1747
01:10:16,946 --> 01:10:19,114
This is very tender too.

1748
01:10:19,181 --> 01:10:21,016
It'll compare directly
with blackthroat seaperch.

1749
01:10:21,083 --> 01:10:23,819
It must've become tender
as it got steamed inside.

1750
01:10:23,886 --> 01:10:26,989
I see. I hope it's better
than blackthroat seaperch.

1751
01:10:27,056 --> 01:10:28,824
A threeline grunt.

1752
01:10:29,892 --> 01:10:31,227
Whoa.

1753
01:10:31,293 --> 01:10:33,095
This fish is like

1754
01:10:33,162 --> 01:10:34,997
Spanish mackerel. Do you know what it is?

1755
01:10:35,064 --> 01:10:36,198
-Yes.
-Of course.

1756
01:10:36,265 --> 01:10:38,100
Of course, you do. I'm sorry.

1757
01:10:38,167 --> 01:10:41,437
-We do.
-We eat Spanish mackerel.

1758
01:10:41,503 --> 01:10:44,340
Blackthroat seaperch
melted in my mouth and disappeared,

1759
01:10:44,406 --> 01:10:46,942
but threeline grunt is dense
like Spanish mackerel.

1760
01:10:47,009 --> 01:10:49,111
-I see.
-And it has the fatty taste too?

1761
01:10:49,178 --> 01:10:51,647
I like the smell of this fish better.

1762
01:10:51,714 --> 01:10:53,415
More than the other one?

1763
01:10:53,482 --> 01:10:54,583
You can smell the fat.

1764
01:10:54,650 --> 01:10:57,886
-He cooked it by locking up the steam.
-You're right.

1765
01:10:57,953 --> 01:10:59,888
-He moved it there.
-Yes, in the oven.

1766
01:10:59,955 --> 01:11:01,323
WHAT WILL HAPPEN TO HIM?

1767
01:11:01,390 --> 01:11:04,860
The sauce is still delicious
even when the three are mixed up.

1768
01:11:04,927 --> 01:11:07,663
-Venus clam.
-Venus clam. He tries a Venus clam.

1769
01:11:07,730 --> 01:11:08,664
He tries it with the sauce.

1770
01:11:09,999 --> 01:11:11,000
How is it?

1771
01:11:11,066 --> 01:11:13,135
HIS FROWN OF TRUTH IS BACK

1772
01:11:13,202 --> 01:11:14,470
What is it?

1773
01:11:14,536 --> 01:11:15,904
I'm so glad I got this.

1774
01:11:15,971 --> 01:11:18,474
-Was the ingredient fresh?
-Yes.

1775
01:11:18,540 --> 01:11:21,143
-He complimented himself.
-Instead of the chef.

1776
01:11:21,210 --> 01:11:24,079
-It wasn't about the chef.
-It wasn't.

1777
01:11:24,146 --> 01:11:25,614
Chef Sung-jun's dish

1778
01:11:25,681 --> 01:11:28,951
brought out the flavor
in the ingredients even more.

1779
01:11:29,018 --> 01:11:31,887
Chef Nam-no's dish was

1780
01:11:31,954 --> 01:11:34,990
<i>more centered around the sauce.</i>

1781
01:11:35,057 --> 01:11:39,595
That's the key difference
between Italian and French cuisines.

1782
01:11:40,929 --> 01:11:42,831
-I see.
-That was precise.

1783
01:11:42,898 --> 01:11:44,099
Is that right, Chef Sam?

1784
01:11:44,166 --> 01:11:48,537
Yes, cartoccio may taste bland
compared to his dish,

1785
01:11:48,604 --> 01:11:52,174
but it probably brought out
the ingredients' flavor.

1786
01:11:52,241 --> 01:11:55,611
Italian cuisine tries to bring out
the ingredients' flavor,

1787
01:11:55,678 --> 01:11:58,247
whereas French cuisine
tries to add delicious sauces.

1788
01:11:58,314 --> 01:11:59,748
-Have you had the stalked sea squirt?
-Yes.

1789
01:11:59,815 --> 01:12:01,283
What was that like?

1790
01:12:02,351 --> 01:12:03,452
It was just a stalked sea squirt.

1791
01:12:04,453 --> 01:12:06,522
A stalked sea squirt
tastes like stalked sea squirt.

1792
01:12:06,588 --> 01:12:08,691
It means
he brought out the natural flavor.

1793
01:12:08,757 --> 01:12:11,360
One of them needs to leave
for the hair salon as soon as we're done.

1794
01:12:11,427 --> 01:12:13,962
Yes, my gosh.

1795
01:12:14,029 --> 01:12:17,333
You can take your time
and eat both dishes.

1796
01:12:17,399 --> 01:12:20,736
Let's hear a word
from Park Byung-eun, the avid fisher.

1797
01:12:20,803 --> 01:12:23,105
He knows all about these fishes.

1798
01:12:23,172 --> 01:12:24,640
Blackthroat seaperch.

1799
01:12:26,675 --> 01:12:28,043
MMM

1800
01:12:28,110 --> 01:12:31,680
The fish itself is fresh and light.

1801
01:12:31,747 --> 01:12:33,916
The executive director is happy.

1802
01:12:33,982 --> 01:12:35,851
He looks like a food critic.

1803
01:12:35,918 --> 01:12:38,520
-Like <i>Solitary Gourmet.</i>
-Yes.

1804
01:12:38,587 --> 01:12:39,555
Mr. Goro.

1805
01:12:39,621 --> 01:12:42,658
-This was the snail replacement.
-Yes.

1806
01:12:43,325 --> 01:12:44,660
The snail replacement.

1807
01:12:44,727 --> 01:12:47,096
Horned turbans are very sweet.

1808
01:12:47,162 --> 01:12:48,263
Isn't it good?

1809
01:12:48,330 --> 01:12:50,766
He shows a huge smile.

1810
01:12:50,833 --> 01:12:52,701
The texture split into three.

1811
01:12:52,768 --> 01:12:54,870
-Three?
-The front is a bit tough,

1812
01:12:54,937 --> 01:12:57,539
but it becomes more tender
as it reaches the inside.

1813
01:12:57,606 --> 01:13:01,176
It's harder on my left cheek
and softer on my right cheek.

1814
01:13:01,243 --> 01:13:03,379
-It's really good.
-You must like the texture.

1815
01:13:03,445 --> 01:13:07,249
I also chewed on almonds
as I ate the seafood.

1816
01:13:07,316 --> 01:13:11,053
The nuttiness of almonds hide
the fishy smell that could've remained.

1817
01:13:11,120 --> 01:13:13,489
When we eat Pyongyang-style <i>naengmyeon,</i>

1818
01:13:13,555 --> 01:13:17,025
we'd find a few pieces of green onion
now and then, right?

1819
01:13:17,092 --> 01:13:20,362
And it refreshes your mouth
whenever you chew on it.

1820
01:13:20,429 --> 01:13:22,364
It was just like that.

1821
01:13:22,431 --> 01:13:23,499
Noryangjin Matfia.

1822
01:13:23,565 --> 01:13:25,701
I personally love threeline grunts.

1823
01:13:25,768 --> 01:13:27,970
I like it both raw and grilled.

1824
01:13:28,036 --> 01:13:30,339
I wonder what this will be like.

1825
01:13:30,406 --> 01:13:32,474
HOW WILL BYUNG-EUN LIKE THIS?

1826
01:13:32,541 --> 01:13:34,643
He talks like a critic.

1827
01:13:35,377 --> 01:13:36,745
NODDING

1828
01:13:36,812 --> 01:13:38,247
It's much denser.

1829
01:13:38,313 --> 01:13:40,749
I can sense that fishy smell,

1830
01:13:40,816 --> 01:13:42,618
but not in a bad way.

1831
01:13:42,684 --> 01:13:45,921
It's the kind of good smell
you'd expect when you eat fish.

1832
01:13:45,988 --> 01:13:47,790
It tastes like fresh fish.

1833
01:13:47,856 --> 01:13:50,259
The sauce is quite interesting.

1834
01:13:50,325 --> 01:13:53,562
The flavor changes
when it moves from red to green

1835
01:13:53,629 --> 01:13:56,999
and when it goes
from red, white, and then green.

1836
01:13:57,065 --> 01:13:58,734
THE EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR(?)
NOTICES SUCH DETAILS

1837
01:13:58,801 --> 01:14:03,672
Everything he says is very intriguing.

1838
01:14:03,739 --> 01:14:06,208
-Like Byung-eun's travel log in the sea.
-Yes.

1839
01:14:07,309 --> 01:14:09,645
-I'm enjoying it so much.
-He's enjoying it.

1840
01:14:09,711 --> 01:14:12,314
Gosh, I wonder
who'll end up at the hair salon.

1841
01:14:12,381 --> 01:14:15,083
It's finally time to decide.

1842
01:14:15,150 --> 01:14:17,419
<i>Press one for Yoon Nam-no</i>

1843
01:14:17,486 --> 01:14:19,288
<i>and two for Kwon Sung-jun.</i>

1844
01:14:19,855 --> 01:14:22,157
Make your decision and press the button.

1845
01:14:22,224 --> 01:14:24,259
-I did.
-Already?

1846
01:14:24,326 --> 01:14:26,128
-Already?
-He's quite fast.

1847
01:14:26,195 --> 01:14:27,763
I thought it'd take him a while.

1848
01:14:28,630 --> 01:14:31,300
<i>I thought about it for a while.</i>
<i>I kept thinking.</i>

1849
01:14:31,366 --> 01:14:34,403
Now, let's find out the result. Show us!

1850
01:14:34,470 --> 01:14:36,104
This is exciting.

1851
01:14:36,171 --> 01:14:38,874
-D.O.ryangjin Fish Market.
-I can't watch this. What do I do?

1852
01:14:38,941 --> 01:14:40,709
It was a round between two military cooks.

1853
01:14:40,776 --> 01:14:43,579
Will it be Sung-jun or Nam-no?

1854
01:14:43,645 --> 01:14:46,348
Who'll have to change his hair?

1855
01:14:46,415 --> 01:14:48,951
-It's the fellow military cook's choice.
-His choice.

1856
01:14:49,017 --> 01:14:50,519
Which one did he choose?

1857
01:14:51,086 --> 01:14:52,254
Who won?

1858
01:14:52,321 --> 01:14:54,890
Who's the winner of the seafood round?

1859
01:14:54,957 --> 01:14:56,058
Who's the winner?

1860
01:14:56,892 --> 01:14:59,261
Who is it?

1861
01:14:59,328 --> 01:15:00,329
YOON NAM-NO WINS

1862
01:15:00,395 --> 01:15:01,997
CHEF NAM-NO GETS TO KEEP HIS HAIR

1863
01:15:02,064 --> 01:15:03,832
It was Yoon Nam-no!

1864
01:15:04,633 --> 01:15:06,001
Oh, no, Sung-jun.

1865
01:15:06,068 --> 01:15:08,303
-He takes the victory.
-Really?

1866
01:15:08,370 --> 01:15:11,273
-He wins against Sung-jun.
-What now?

1867
01:15:11,340 --> 01:15:13,742
Sung-jun loses this round.

1868
01:15:13,809 --> 01:15:16,144
I had a single reason.

1869
01:15:16,211 --> 01:15:17,679
-One reason?
-Yes.

1870
01:15:17,746 --> 01:15:20,082
-It was the scallops.
-Scallops?

1871
01:15:20,148 --> 01:15:24,620
Chef Sung-jun's scallops were
large and thick,

1872
01:15:24,686 --> 01:15:28,357
<i>-but Chef Nam-no's were thin.</i>
<i>-He sliced them thinly.</i>

1873
01:15:28,423 --> 01:15:32,928
So these thick ones were
a little tougher to eat.

1874
01:15:32,995 --> 01:15:35,297
-That was the only reason.
-Right?

1875
01:15:35,364 --> 01:15:38,500
If the scallops were sliced thinly,

1876
01:15:38,567 --> 01:15:40,335
I couldn't have left today.

1877
01:15:40,402 --> 01:15:43,739
That was why eating scallop
hurt your scalp-o.

1878
01:15:43,805 --> 01:15:45,507
-It'd hurt.
-It was a matter of scallops.

1879
01:15:45,574 --> 01:15:47,175
-A matter of scallops.
-Let's hear from him.

1880
01:15:48,844 --> 01:15:51,313
Even rice paddles come
in different levels and classes.

1881
01:15:51,380 --> 01:15:52,881
There's always a difference.

1882
01:15:52,948 --> 01:15:56,084
Please don't consider us
the same kind of military cooks.

1883
01:15:56,151 --> 01:15:57,586
You're not all the same.

1884
01:15:57,653 --> 01:16:00,789
What will you do now, Chef Sung-jun?

1885
01:16:00,856 --> 01:16:02,357
I'll buy a can of beer

1886
01:16:02,424 --> 01:16:04,893
on my way home today to bleach my hair.

1887
01:16:04,960 --> 01:16:06,428
WELCOME TO THE WORLD OF BLEACHED HAIR

1888
01:16:06,495 --> 01:16:08,297
Congratulations, Chef Nam-no.

1889
01:16:08,363 --> 01:16:10,465
-Congratulations.
-Congratulations.

1890
01:16:10,532 --> 01:16:12,601
A round between two friends.

1891
01:16:12,668 --> 01:16:15,938
Their fellow military cook chose
Yoon Nam-no!

1892
01:16:16,004 --> 01:16:17,506
-Congratulations.
-Congratulations.

1893
01:16:17,573 --> 01:16:19,207
-Great work.
-Yes.

1894
01:16:20,742 --> 01:16:24,212
He has more photos of fish
than himself on his social media account.

1895
01:16:24,279 --> 01:16:26,114
I've caught over 500 webfoot octopuses.

1896
01:16:26,181 --> 01:16:28,850
You can even sell it to businesses.

1897
01:16:28,917 --> 01:16:31,019
-Those are all yours?
-I like to enjoy drinks.

1898
01:16:31,086 --> 01:16:32,154
You need to see this.

1899
01:16:32,220 --> 01:16:35,324
-People call this kind of liquor medicine.
-Is he here to sell those?

1900
01:16:35,390 --> 01:16:36,458
How much is that?

1901
01:16:36,525 --> 01:16:38,093
I can't put a number on it.

1902
01:16:38,160 --> 01:16:39,394
THE FRIDGE SALESMAN TAKES THE STAGE

1903
01:16:39,461 --> 01:16:40,629
He's so good at sales.

1904
01:16:40,696 --> 01:16:42,564
<i>I've been on a roll</i>
<i>whenever I used seafood.</i>

1905
01:16:42,631 --> 01:16:44,533
<i>Many Italian dishes are made with seafood.</i>

1906
01:16:44,600 --> 01:16:45,667
<i>The ingredients look excellent.</i>

1907
01:16:45,734 --> 01:16:46,868
That's cutlassfish.

1908
01:16:46,935 --> 01:16:48,270
About four fingers and a half.

1909
01:16:48,337 --> 01:16:49,638
He sounds like a salesman.

1910
01:16:49,705 --> 01:16:51,073
Come on, Executive Director.

1911
01:16:51,139 --> 01:16:53,175
<i>I have to fight him to rise up.</i>

1912
01:16:53,241 --> 01:16:55,377
<i>I like fighting a strong chef head-on.</i>

1913
01:16:55,444 --> 01:16:56,712
This is a big match.

1914
01:16:56,778 --> 01:16:58,647
Executive Director Park
deserves delicious food.

1915
01:16:58,714 --> 01:17:00,282
EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR PARK IS PLEASED

1916
01:17:00,349 --> 01:17:01,583
A present from the executive director!

1917
01:17:01,650 --> 01:17:02,985
This is nice.

1918
01:17:03,051 --> 01:17:04,453
-Chief Poong.
-Chief Poong.

1919
01:17:04,519 --> 01:17:06,188
Go home if you're drunk.

1920
01:17:06,254 --> 01:17:09,424
-Until the day you become the CEO!
-I'm liking you more and more.

1921
01:17:09,491 --> 01:17:11,860
-Cheers!
-Cheers!

1922
01:17:11,927 --> 01:17:13,495
<i>How about</i> makgeolli <i>later?</i>

1923
01:17:13,562 --> 01:17:15,030
Makgeolli <i>sounds good.</i>

1924
